<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Trade Minister Meets French Trade Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 27 (Xinhua) -- China will unswervingly
continue to carry out its policy of reform and opening-up, Chinese
Foreign Trade Minister Wu Yi said during a meeting here this
afternoon with Yves Galland, minister-delegate to France's
Ministry of Economics and Finance.
</P>
<P>
Galland, in charge of finance and foreign trade, came to China
to prepare for the visit by French President Jacques Chirac to
China this May.
</P>
<P>
On behalf of the French Government, Galland expressed
condolences over the death of Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping.
</P>
<P>
Wu, minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation, said,
"The death of Deng is a great loss to the cause of reform and
opening-up in China. The Chinese people, however, will turn grief
into strength and continue to fulfill the cause initiated by
Comrade Deng, under the strong leadership of the third generation
of the collective leadership of the Chinese Communist Party with
Comrade Jiang Zemin at the core."
</P>
<P>
She said China attaches great importance to developing its
economic and trade relations with France, and looks forward to
smooth bilateral cooperation in the fields of aviation and power.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from China's General Administration of Customs show
that the volume of Sino-French trade reached 4.15 billion US
dollars-worth last year, with China's exports standing at 1.907
billion US dollars-worth and imports at 2.24 billion US
dollars-worth. Galland, however, said that his country has a trade
deficit.
</P>
<P>
It is not surprising for one country to have deficits vis-a-vis
some countries while having surpluses vis-a-vis others, Wu noted.
</P>
<P>
Quarrels won't help resolve any problems, Wu pointed out,
adding that China adheres to the policy of seeking balance through
development and insists on settlement of problems through equal
and friendly negotiations.
</P>
<P>
She said China attaches great importance to Chirac's visit and
Chinese businessmen are willing to work with their French
counterparts to create an ideal atmosphere for the visit.
</P>
<P>
Galland said France was one of the first countries to recognize
the People's Republic of China and highly values its ties with
China, especially in the economic and trade sphere.
</P>
<P>
Both sides exchanged views on the 12th session of the
Sino-French economic and trade joint committee and the issue of
anti-dumping.
</P>
<P>
Wu said China highly values its economic and trade ties with
the European Union (EU), its third-biggest trading partner. She
added that China resolutely opposes the EU's discriminative
limitations on some Chinese products and hopes that France will do
something for the settlement of the problem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
