<HEADLINE> Pakistan Proposes Talks With India on Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Prime Minister
Nawaz Sharif today proposed Foreign Secretary level talks with
India on the issue of Kashmir before the end of March as a prelude
to the Prime Ministerial level talks.
</P>
<P>
The proposed talks are to "prepare ground for meaningful
discussion at Prime Ministerial level talks as early as possible,"
Sharif said in reply to a letter from Indian Prime Minister Deve
Gowda.
</P>
<P>
He hoped Gowda would agree with him that "without some progress
on the core issue of Jammu and Kashmir it will be difficult to
initiate cooperation in economic and cultural fields."
</P>
<P>
"As we approach the 50th anniversary of our independence, there
is a historic opportunity for the political leadership of both the
countries to deal with all the outstanding disputes which bedevil
our relations," Sharif said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
