<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sampras Sees HK as Chance for Consolidating No. 1 Position </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- As world number one tennis
player, Pete Sampras sees the coming Salem Open '97 in Hong Kong
as much more than just another stop of the year's ATP Tour.
</P>
<P>
A win at the tournament, which is the only ATP Tour World
Series event in Hong Kong to award world-ranking points, will keep
the 25-year-old right-hander at the top of the ATP Tour rankings
and push him to overtake compatriots John McEnroe and Jimmy
Connors in the record books.
</P>
<P>
But before reaching that height, Sampras has to overcome his
arch rival and 25-year-old compatriot Michael Chang, who has also
something to prove at this year's tournament, slated for April
5-13. The third-ranked Chang is desperate to win again in Asia,
following a disappointing year in the region in 1996. He failed
to pick up an Asian title for the first time since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Sampras has finished the last four years at the top, joining
the ranks of McEnroe and Connors; and to finish 1997 in the top
spot will underline his status as one of the greatest players of
the Open era to finish at the top of the ATP Tour rankings for
five consecutive years.
</P>
<P>
Along with Sampras and Chang, other players expected to play
key roles in the 328,000 U.S. dollars event include Switzerland's
big-serving former Olympic champion Marc Rosset, who is now ranked
16th in the world, and three Australians -- Todd Woodbridge,
ranked 26th, his doubles partner and 50th-ranked Mark Woodforde
and Patrick Rafter, who will be making his third appearance in
four years at Salem Open, having reached the final in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A total of 32 players are entered in the main draw for the
singles and the event also includes a 16-pair doubles
competition. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
