<HEADLINE> Russia Seeks Best Compromise of NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian leaders have
quietly taken a more pragmatic approach to the planned eastward
expansion of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, a U.S.
newspaper reported today.
</P>
<P>
"In recent months, Russia has taken a two-tiered approach to
NATO's planned enlargement to include Poland, Hungary and the
Czech Republic by 1999," The Washington Post reported.
</P>
<P>
One level was a vigorous public campaign by all the Russians
against the expansion. The second track was to be ready to
negotiate a compromise, the paper added.
</P>
<P>
"Now Russia seems to be putting fresh emphasis on the second
approach," the report said, quoting a Western diplomat as saying,
"Their tact has been to protest loudly and then crawl back."
</P>
<P>
"This is a negotiating game, and the Russians will try and get
as much as they can," the diplomat said.
</P>
<P>
NATO planned to list the first group of countries that will be
allowed to join the alliance at its special summit in Madrid in
July.
</P>
<P>
Russia, which says that the alliance's enlargement will divide
Europe and create a new Cold War, strongly opposes NATO's plan.
</P>
<P>
Shuttle diplomacy by both sides has undergone between capitals
of NATO members and Moscow. However, no breakthrough has been
reached in the row. 
</P>
</TEXT>
