<HEADLINE> Manila, Rebels Agree to Form Panel to Monitor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Peace negotiators from the
Philippine government and the Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF)
rebels today reached an agreement to form an independent panel to
monitor their ceasefire in clashed areas in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was reached after the two sides had three days of
preliminary talks in Cotabato, Maguindanao province, the southern
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
It was their second round of low-level talks, during which the
two parties also agreed to have another round of talks in a bid to
seek a full and permanent ceasefire in the MILF-controlled areas.
</P>
<P>
The official Philippine Television (PTV) reported that the
initial members of the independent panel will come from the media,
an education peace center, a lawyers league and some religious
groups.
</P>
<P>
The MILF is a breakaway faction of the mainstream Moro National
Liberation Front which signed a peace agreement with the
government last year, ending a 24-year-old civil war in Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that sporadic clashes between government troops
and MILF rebels occurred in Buldon, Maguindanao, last month,
killing at least 40 people. Later on, the two sides reached a
temporary ceasefire and decided to hold preliminary peace talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
