<HEADLINE> EU Calls for Direct Negotiations in Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- European Union (EU)
Commissioner for External Relations Hans van den Broek today
called on the Greek and Turkish Cypriot sides to embark on
comprehensive talks to end the division of Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
The EU commissioner, who arrived here Wednesday night, made
the remarks today after meeting with Cyprus President Glafcos
Clerides.
</P>
<P>
"If there is and remains separation, the country will be in
constant conflict and there will be others outside the country
benefiting from the hostile situation," Van den Broek warned.
</P>
<P>
Expressing support for "each and every effort to get an
opening of negotiations," the commissioner said "I reconfirm the
EU commitment toward the president to start accession
negotiations next year and underline how important it is to see
some perspective and some movement by that time on the political
side."
</P>
<P>
This, he said, would make accession negotiations much
easier and could conclude them probably much sooner.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Turkish Cypriot participation in the process
of accession, the commissioner said most EU member states have
expressed a wish to see the Turkish Cypriots involved in the
accession talks.
</P>
<P>
He invited the Turkish Cypriots to show their own initiatives
to facilitate a solution to the Cyprus problem and assist their
participation in the accession process.
</P>
<P>
Van den Broek said he will explain to the Turkish Cypriots
that they can benefit from EU funds and the single European
market as well as increased tourism.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, a structured dialogue between the EU and Cyprus
was postponed in Brussels following disagreement among EU member
states over Turkish Cypriot participation.
</P>
<P>
Britain, France and Germany made a proposal insisting the
inclusion of phrases in the EU document calling for the
participation of all Cypriots in the accession process.
</P>
<P>
But Greece rejected the document and warned that the EU would
pay a price for its demands.
</P>
<P>
Cyprus, which has remained divided since 1974, applied for
full EU membership in 1990. 
</P>
</TEXT>
