<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3Com Plans to Acquire US Robotics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The 3Com Corporation, a major
network company of the U.S., will acquire the U.S. Robotics
Corporation in a 6.6 billion U.S. dollar stock swap that will
create the second-largest computer networking company.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported today that acquisition would
strengthen 3Com's power against competitors, particularly Cisco
Systems Inc., the leader in computer networking, by broadening its
product line.
</P>
<P>
While 3Com, based in Santa Clara, California, is a market
leader in local area network equipment, best known for its
Ethernet adaptor cards, which connect personal computers to local
area networks, it has lagged behind in wide area network devices,
which connect over much longer distances. U.S. Robotics, however,
is a major maker of remote access servers, which handle incoming
calls at services like America Online.
</P>
<P>
Share prices of both companies went up Wednesday on the Nasdaq
market, with U.S. Robotics surging 17 percent.
</P>
<P>
Under the terms of the deal, each share of U.S. Robotics' stock
will be exchanged for 1.75 shares of 3Com stock, which is valued
according to the closing prices Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said the deal was essentially a merger of equals. But
they added the deal made good strategic sense for both companies.
Ever since Cisco went from being a router company to a company
that offered a full line of networking devices, mostly by
acquiring a string of companies, competitors in the field have
struggled to keep up.
</P>
<P>
The combined company would have 5 billion U.S. dollars in
revenues and more than 12,000 employees. U.S. Robotics' Chicago
headquarters will become a division of 3Com.
</P>
<P>
The deal will put additional pressure on competitors. The
networking market is already brutally competitive, analysts said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Durable Goods Orders Increase in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Orders to U.S. factories
for durable goods surged by 3.6 percent in January, the largest
increase since last September, the U.S. Commerce Department
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department said that orders for durable goods totaled a
seasonally adjusted 174.8 billion dollars, up from 168.8 billion
in December.
</P>
<P>
The report also revised December's orders to a 1.8 percent drop
from the earlier estimated decline of 1.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
It showed that each of the major categories shared the gain in
January, including a double-digit increase in electronic and other
electrical equipment.
</P>
<P>
Transportation orders rose by 1.2 percent in January, erasing a
0.9 percent loss a month earlier. Increases in motor vehicles and
airplanes more than offset decreases in shipbuilding, tanks and
railroad equipment.
</P>
<P>
Excluding transportation, orders were up by 4.4 percent, the
first increase in four months.
</P>
<P>
Unfilled orders, which were unchanged in December, increased by
0.8 percent, the eighth increase in the last nine months. A
growing backlog suggests businesses could find it necessary to
increase production facilities and manpower to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a measure of current activity, rose by 1.2 percent
following the 0.9 percent decline in December.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods are a key gauge of the U.S.
manufacturing sector. Continued growth could lead to increased
production and more jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
