<BODY>
<HEADLINE> France Withdraws Military Advisors From Central Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- France today announced the
withdrawal of its advisors for the Central African presidential
security service, following two days of anti-French riots in the
Central African capital of Bangui by militant supporters of
President Ange-Felix Patasse.
</P>
<P>
Pierre Servent, an advisor to French Defense Minister Charles
Millon, said that the French advisors for the presidential
security service, estimated at 23 by the local daily Liberation,
were withdrawn because the situation in Central Africa had been
"improved."
</P>
<P>
"The presidential security service should evolve in the medium
term toward a republican guard which will better reflect the
appeal for national union launched by President Patasse
recently," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also announced that all the French soldiers stationed in
Bangui have returned to their barracks, except those in charge of
protecting the French embassy and the residence of the French
ambassador.
</P>
<P>
France now maintains 1,800 soldiers in Central Africa,
including 1,200 in Bangui.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) reported that over the past two
days, French civilians and their cars were attacked with stones in
Bangui, while anti-French pamphlets were distributed by the
militants of the presidential party, the Movement of Liberation of
the Central-African People (MLPC).
</P>
<P>
The secretary general of the MLPC, Joseph Vermond Tchendo,
appealed on television Wednesday night for calm, and asked the
MLPC militants to "cease throwing stones on foreigners, no matter
whether they are black or white."
</P>
<P>
Most of the incidents took place on a highway between the
Bangui airport, near which there is an air base used by the French
troops, and the headquarters of the MLPC. The road is frequented by
French military men and civilians, said AFP.
</P>
<P>
It is not clear why the riots broke out, in which no one was
seriously injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
