<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Regional Integration Key to Trade: COMESA </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Efforts to promote economic
integration should be speeded-up if countries in the region are
to compete in the global economy, a COMESA official said here
today.
</P>
<P>
Addressing delegates at a two-day meeting on international
trade finance, Executive Secretary of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) bankers association Davison
Marape said the world was changing, with economic blocs being
formed everywhere.
</P>
<P>
"Consolidation of our regional cooperation and integration
would enable us to develop our industries, attract foreign
investment and create employment for our ever-increasing
populations," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the meeting, which ends on Friday, aimed at providing
information to participants about trade financing techniques,
banking guarantees and inherent risks in these operations.
</P>
<P>
Marape said commercial banks required a strong forum at
national and regional levels to enable them to extend their
activities and participate in the economic development of the
sub-region.
</P>
<P>
The seminar was attended by representatives of the 10 members
of the association, namely Burundi, Ethiopia, Kenya, Malawi,
Rwanda, Sudan, Swaziland, Tanzania, Uganda and Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
