<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dutch Economy in Right Track in 1996: Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Most recent figures show that
the Dutch economy is heading in the right direction, with the
gross domestic product in the Netherlands growing last year by 2.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
The Dutch economy is now more broadly based, with all
categories of expenditure contributing to the growth in GDP in the
second half of last year, Statistics Netherlands reported today in
its Economic Outlook.
</P>
<P>
The estimates for the growth in the volume of industrial
production in 1996 point to stable growth. Though the growth of
the construction industry is lagging behind that in the
manufacturing industry, the figure last year was the highest for
eight years.
</P>
<P>
Household consumer spending rose sharply in 1996 to record the
highest growth rate since 1991. The volume of consumer credit in
1996 totaled over 16 billion guilders (10.7 billion U.S. dollars),
an increase of 14.4 percent on 1995 -- the largest in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Private individuals were highly active in borrowing, saving and
investing in 1996 and share prices set one record after another.
The average savings balances held by private individuals with
savings institutions rose by 7 percent in 1996.
</P>
<P>
In the first half of 1996, household consumption was the main
motive force for GDP growth. In the second half of the year, the
other expenditure categories -- international trade and investment
-- also contributed positively to growth.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the volume of industrial production in
1996 was 2.0 percent up on the year before, when industrial
production rose by 2.3 percent. By contrast, production falls were
recorded in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The largest rise in output occurred last year in the textiles,
clothing and leather industry and the metal industry. A fall in
added value was recorded in 1996 in the chemical industry and the
rubber and plastics industry.
</P>
<P>
The volume of merchandise exports rose by 4.1 percent, and the
volume of imports by 3.9 percent, less than in 1994 and 1995. The
report on the economy also noted an increase in gross investment
in machines of over 5 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
