<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McDonald's Corporation to Stem Slide in US Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW York, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The McDdonald's Corporation,
the largest fast-food company in the United States, is trying to
stem slide in the domestic market by cutting prices, according to
a report of the New York Times today.
</P>
<P>
The company, frustrated by steady market share gains by its
leading rivals in the country, plans to slash prices on selected
items on a rotating basis. Initially, the Big Mac burger that now
sells for about two U.S. dollars would be cut to about 55 cents
when purchased along with fries and a drink.
</P>
<P>
For the last six quarters, sales at McDonald's open a year or
more have fallen though its business outside the United States has
been booming.
</P>
<P>
The company's domestic sales jumped from 10.6 billion U.S.
dollars in 1987 to nearly 16.4 billion U.S. dollars last year, but
its overall fast-food market share fell from 17.8 percent to 16.1
percent.
</P>
<P>
The competition comes from Burger King and several new quick
service players, including the rapidly expanding bagel chains.
</P>
<P>
Analysts and experts said that McDonald's action raised the
possibility of a fast-food price war. And investors on Wall Street
generally feared that a wave of price cutting would lead to lower
profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
