<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: Future of Bangladesh's Leather Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's leather industry,
the country's fifth biggest foreign exchange earner, is in the
doldrums due to a lack of funds and technical know-how, local
producers and exporters warn.
</P>
<P>
Export earnings from the leather sector slumped to 92.29
million U.S. dollars during July-December of the current fiscal
year, a 14 percent drop compared with the previous corresponding
period.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, exports of finished leather
are estimated to be about 17.28 million square feet annually,
accounting for only 10-11 percent of the total leather processed
in the country.
</P>
<P>
Bangladesh may lose an additional 75 million U.S. dollars
annually due to the slow conversion into finished leather from
crust leather, leather experts estimated.
</P>
<P>
The major constraints in expansion of finished leather
production are lack of working capital, requisite technology and
marketing experience, said the experts.
</P>
<P>
The nature of the industry requires the holding of large
inventories of raw hides and imported chemicals due to seasonal
variation in supply, which means large working capital.
</P>
<P>
"Unfortunately, the bank support to our industry is far from
satisfactory," complained Garib Newaz, a leading leather producer,
adding that the crisis of working capital precludes entrepreneurs
from long term investment to increase the quality of leather.
</P>
<P>
In fact, Leaders of Bangladesh Finished Leather Exporter's
Association and Leather Goods Manufacturers Association have
recently submitted a joint memorandum to the Industries and
Commerce Minister Toafel Ahmed demanding fresh credit for the
capital-starved industry.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, most of the finished leather exporters lack
marketing experience, which often results in a low level of
capacity utilization.
</P>
<P>
There is also an acute shortage of qualified tanners, resulting
in low-quality output and a high percentage of damaged raw
material.
</P>
<P>
As slaughtering is done by unskilled butchers in most
tanneries, the hides and skin are damaged with flay cuts, scratch
marks and loss of area, which downgrades the quality.
</P>
<P>
Although modern machinery is equipped to a good number of
tanneries, the proper use of them cannot be ensured due to lack of
technical and skilled manpower.
</P>
<P>
"As there is little chance of increased supply of leather, more
value addition should be emphasized," said local exporters, noting
that only 200 million square feet of crust and finished leather is
produced annually in 65 tanneries throughout the country.
</P>
<P>
Expressing optimism, they said export earnings could reach at
least 650 million U.S. dollars by transporting leather into
leather goods.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the goals, more training centers and institutions
should be installed to produce skilled professionals and ensure
quality production, they added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0023 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investment From Developing Asia on Rise in Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Foreign direct investment (FDI)
in Europe by Asian developing economies reached an average 860
million US dollars during 1992-94 with 40 percent of the European
Union's stock going to Britain, according to an UN's report
released here today.
</P>
<P>
The investment total compared with just 100 million US dollars
in 1989-91, said the United Nations Conference on Trade and
Development (UNCTAD) in the report entitled "Sharing Asia's
Dynamism: Asian Direct Investment in the European Union."
</P>
<P>
Many firms of the Asian newly industrializing economies (NIEs)
increasingly see need for a direct presence in the EU in order to
serve this large and rich market, the report said.
</P>
<P>
Others are seeking access to advanced technology and skills,
research and development programs, it added.
</P>
<P>
While North America remains Asian NIEs' main investment
location beyond Asia, their activities in the EU have gathered
momentum, both in manufacturing and services.
</P>
<P>
Investment projects in the two sectors were located in Britain
ahead of any other country and Britain also hosted Asian
investment in all major services industries.
</P>
<P>
Direct investment in electronics accounted for three-quarters
of all manufacturing projects from Hong Kong, Korea, Singapore and
Taiwan, with Britain again claiming the largest share.
</P>
<P>
Nearly three-quarters of Korean investment alone in Europe --
worth a total of 1 billion US dollars in 1995 -- was in electrical
and electronic products.
</P>
<P>
Hong Kong was said to be the most important investor among the
Asian developing economies in the EU with 1.3 billion US dollars
in FDI stock in 1994.
</P>
<P>
However, 30 percent of its FDI in the EU actually originated
from other economies and most Hong Kong FDI in the EU was in
wholesale and retail trade.
</P>
<P>
"Taiwan ranks second among Asian developing economies in terms
of FDI inflows into the European Union. As in the case of other
Asian newly industrializing economies, investors are attracted
mainly by Britain," the report said.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Taiwanese FDI stock in the EU (over 250
billion US dollars in 1994) was located in Britain, it added.
</P>
<P>
More than half of Singapore's total FDI abroad was in financial
services with only 20 percent in manufacturing, such as Mayor
PTE's electronic components plant in Britain.
</P>
<P>
North America remains the main investment location beyond Asia.
However, the activities of Asian developing economies in the EU
have gathered momentum.
</P>
<P>
The share of the EU in the total FDI stock from developing Asia
reached about 5 percent in 1995. Though this is still relatively
low, the UNCTAD observes that this does "not reflect neglect, but
rather the fact that Asian firms are just at the beginning of
their entry into Europe." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
