<HEADLINE> New York City's Economic Performance Lags Behind </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 27 (Xinhua) -- New York City, which
benefited in 1996 from the effect of a record year in the stock
market, lags far behind most of the nation's cities in overall
economic performance, a city report said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In three key measures of economic health -- unemployment, job
growth and the local rate of inflation -- New York City was among
the nation's weakest urban economies, according to the report
issued by the City Comptroller, Alan G. Hevesi.
</P>
<P>
The gross city product, a measures based on total jobs and
income that is similar to the national gross domestic product,
still lagged in the nation, rising only 1.9 percent for the year
compared with a national growth rate of 2.5 percent, said the
report, which is said to be the first major full-year economic
assessment of 1996.
</P>
<P>
Of the nation's 20 largest urban centers, the report said, New
York had the highest unemployment rate for the year, 8.6 percent,
and was outpaced by all but five cities in the percentage growth
of new jobs. And its inflation rate for the year, 2.95 percent,
was surpassed by only two cities, Miami and St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the first half of last year saw the
growth in the city, but since July the economy had slowed
dramatically. 
</P>
</TEXT>
