<HEADLINE> Ireland Under Pressure to Amend Bill on Working Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Irish government is under
mounting pressure from U.S. investors to amend a bill adopting the
European Union's (EU) directive of 48-hour working week, according
to reports from Dublin.
</P>
<P>
A number of leading American multinationals, including
Hewlett-Packard, have warned that lack of flexibility in the
proposed legislation will weaken Ireland's competitiveness as a
location for foreign investment.
</P>
<P>
They also argued that the legislation, which is being reviewed
in the Dail (lower house of the Irish parliament), will eventually
result in job losses.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. Chamber of Commerce, which represents more than 400
American companies in Ireland employing 60,000 people, said in a
submission to the Dail that it was "no exaggeration to say" the
bill represented "the single most negative change in the past 20
years" in Ireland's drive to attract U.S. investors.
</P>
<P>
Ireland's recent economic boom has been dependent on foreign
investment, which accounts for 75 percent of manufacturing
exports, around half its manufactured output and 45 percent of
employment in manufacturing.
</P>
<P>
Richard Bruton, the Irish enterprise and employment minister,
is due to hold talks with leading U.S. investors in a bid to
appease opponents of the bill. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
