<HEADLINE> Yeltsin, Chechevatov Discuss Military Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today discussed with Colonel-General Viktor Chechevatov, Commander
of the Far Eastern Military District, about issues of military
reforms.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential Press Office said in a statement, Chechevatov
told the president that difficulty exists in the troops of the Far
Eastern Military District, but he assured him the troops are in
control.
</P>
<P>
Chechevatov added that the troops are going on with regular
trainings despite difficult conditions. But he said it was
necessary to prevent any further decline in their combat
capability and to raise their morale.
</P>
<P>
The commander also called for radical, energetic actions from
the government and the military leadership to implement reforms in
the military.
</P>
<P>
He exchanged views with the president on measures to cope with
NATO's eastward plans. "A rejection in principle of the plans for
the expansion of the alliance was confirmed," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
General Chechevatov was received by the president four times
last year to review Russian military reform in the Far East.
</P>
<P>
Chechevatov decided to run for the Russian presidency in
December 1995, but two months before the polling date, announced
his withdrawal from the race in favor of Boris Yeltsin. 
</P>
