<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> International Conference on Child Labor Ends </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMSTERDAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- An international conference
on child labor ended today here calling for an immediate action to
combat its most intolerable forms such as slavery, debt bondage,
prostitution and work in hazardous industries.
</P>
<P>
Some 200 government ministers, trade union leaders, employer
organizations and representatives of working children attended the
two-day round table conference, which was organized by the Dutch
Government and co-hosted by the International Labor
Organization(ILO).
</P>
<P>
The participants agreed that concerted action is required
through integrated policy approaches towards the progressive
elimination of all child labour, with priority given to its most
intolerable forms.
</P>
<P>
"These intolerable forms of child labor are the first concern
for all of us," said Dutch Social Affairs Minister Ad Melkert,
adding that he is convinced that with joint forces the worst forms
of child labour can be banned.
</P>
<P>
Melkert noted that it is essential to keep track of the
advancements of combating child labor.
</P>
<P>
"I therefore find it desirable that in 1999 countries draw up a
binding agreement to reduce child labor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Melkert also noted that he was in favor of a new agreement,
rather than replacing the ILO's current 1973 Minimum Age
Convention.
</P>
<P>
The ILO estimates that nearly a third of the world's 250
million child labourers work under dangerous or harmful conditions.
</P>
<P>
An ILO report prepared for the conference says tens of millions
of child labourers in South Asia are kept in slavery or under
forced labor systems, such as debt bondage.
</P>
<P>
The report also notes the increasing sexual exploitation of
children and its terrible effects.
</P>
<P>
"Case studies reveal a trauma so deep that many such children
are unable to return to a normal life. Many others die before
adulthood," the ILO says.
</P>
<P>
The conference is a step towards the drafting of a new
international convention on the worst forms of child exploitation,
said Michel Hansenne, ILO Director-General.
</P>
<P>
"We want a new convention in a global context that will be
possible for all the ILO's members to ratify and to comply with,
shall we say, the minimum rules of the game, and the conference
gives us a good opportunity to discuss this," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
