<HEADLINE> Palestinian National Dialogue Held In Nablus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Representatives of Various
Palestinian political groups met in Nablus today to have a
"national dialogue" on the future of Palestine, according to a
report of JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The national dialogue, initiated by Palestinian President
Yasser Arafat, is aimed at setting the ground for a political
consensus between the Palestinian National Authority and
opposition factions and drawing up a national Platform to address
 challenges of the peace process in the future, especially in
the final-status negotiations with Israel.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian Cabinet Secretary Abdul Rahman said to the Voice of
Palestine radio that all factions welcomed the President Yasser
Arafat's call except "those who sold their destiny to Iran
and some other organizations."
</P>
<P>
He did not identify specific factions but praised some
leaders of the Islamic Jihad for attending the national
dialogue, although Islamic Jihad announced boycott of the meeting
in a communique issued Monday.
</P>
<P>
Both President of the Palestine National Council Salim Zanoun
and President of the Palestinian Council Ahmed Qrei' in their
speechs stressed the importance of forming a unified national
front to preserve the PNA achievements and face future
challenges.
</P>
<P>
The national dialogue, arranged quite some time ago, took
place after the Israeli cabinet Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem
 Affairs approved the construction of a new Jewish settlement at
Har Homa in the Arab east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Arafat condemned the decision while speaking to reporters
before the meeting. He said that the Har Homa decision went
against the Oslo Accords, U.N. resolutions and the U.S.
guarantees in a letter attached to the Hebron agreement signed
last month.
</P>
<P>
"The new challenges, launched by (Binyamin) Netanyahu yesterday,
determined the seriousness of this dialogue and finalized a
sacred document wherein all Palestinian forces would comply with
in order to achieve our difficult aims," Zanoun told the Voice of
Palestine radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
