<HEADLINE> Iran to Launch Satellite Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Iranian President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani today announced that Iran is to launch a satellite
project during the new Iranian calendar year starting from March
21, 1997.
</P>
<P>
Official news agency IRNA reported that Rafsanjani made
the announcement in his two-day tour to inaugurate development
and infrastructural projects in the southern port city of Bushehr.
</P>
<P>
The 64-year-old president said that the project for making
the satellite will be carried out jointly by ministries of
post, telegraph and telephone as well as industry and defense.
</P>
<P>
However, he did not reveal whether Iran will use foreign
technology or investment.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Iran said that it was ready to launch a
satellite called Zohreh (Venus) for telecommunication purposes.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the launching of the satellite was on last year's
agenda of the government since President Rafsanjani announced it
in the fiscal budget for 1996.
</P>
<P>
However, the Persian magazine Payam-e Emrouz and other press
did not reveal whether the satellite was imported or made
inside the country.
</P>
<P>
The report did not mention which foreign company would help
Iran launch the satellite because Iran has no capability of
satellite launching.
</P>
<P>
It reported that Iran has been granted three orbits by
International Telecommunication Union (ITU) for its satellite.
</P>
</TEXT>
