<HEADLINE> Talks on Zairean Peace Make Headway: Mandela </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, February 27 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Nelson Mandela said in Pretoria today that progress had been made
in efforts to broker a peace settlement in eastern Zaire.
</P>
<P>
"There is progress that is very encouraging," Mandela told
reporters after meeting Zairean President Mobutu Sese Seko's
special envoy Honore Ngbanda in Pretoria, the administrative
capital of South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Mandela declined to give details of progress made in his talks
with both Ngbanda and visiting Zairean rebel leader Laurent
Kabila who arrived in Johannesburg on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
However, Mandela confirmed that his government had been in
contact with Mobutu, saying Deputy President Thabo Mbeki had met
the Zairean president last week.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his proposed meeting with Mobutu scheduled in
March, Mandela said this was being discussed with Kenyan
President Daniel Arap Moi, who was in charge of the Zairean peace
talks.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot confirm anything until we also have the support of
President Mobutu", Mandela was quoted by South African Press
Association as saying.
</P>
<P>
Ngbanda, who arrived in South African two days ago, also met a
United States delegation led by U.S. Assistant Secretary of State
for African Affairs George Moose.
</P>
<P>
He reiterated on Thursday Mobutu's commitment to finding a
peaceful solution and to saving the lives of innocent people.
This should be done while respecting the territorial sovereignty
of Zaire, Ngbanda said.
</P>
<P>
Multinational talks aimed at ending the Zairean conflict were
reportedly held in Pretoria on Tuesday and Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Zairean rebels launched an offensive last September in attempt
to topple Mobutu's 31-year rule after the government allegedly
tried to expel ethnic tutsis from the east of the country.
</P>
