<HEADLINE> Athens Bourse Drops Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The share prices at the Athens
Stock Exchange dropped sharply today following nine consecutive
days of explosive trading.
</P>
<P>
The general price index closed today at 1367.16 points, down
5.95 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Banks lost 7.27 percent, insurance 3.99 percent, leasing 4.01
percent, investment 6.17 percent, construction 7.19 percent,
industry 5.10 percent, various 6.18 percent and holdings 4.92
percent.
</P>
<P>
The over-the-counter market index dropped by 3.22 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total volume of today's trading was 31 billion drachmas
(124 U.S. million dollars), compared to 45.2 billion drachmas (181
million dollars) Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Bourse sources attributed the sharp drop to statements
Wednesday by President of the Capital Market Committee Stavros
Thomadakis, who expressed concern about the creation of a climate
of "unfair games and speculation" on the Athens Stock Exchange
following recent surges in trading.
</P>
<P>
The National Economy Ministry however assured investors today
that recent developments on the Athens Stock Exchange were
perfectly normal.
</P>
<P>
The ministry's General Secretary Apostolos Fotiadis said, "The
recent positive course of the stock exchange is perfectly normal
and all the prerequisites have been secured for the continuation
of this course."
</P>
<P>
"Political stability, the success of the government's economic
policy, the positive developments with regard to all economic
indicators, the drop in inflation and interest rates, in
combination with our undoubted will to safeguard the credibility
of the institution have contributed decisively in this direction,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
