<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Volcano Erupts in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A volcano has exploded in
one of the mountains on the western side of Gedo region in south
Somalia bordering with Ethiopia, killing a number of goats and
sheep, a report reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
According to Omar Abdi Ahmed, the commissioner of Bohol
Garas town, 40 km northeast of the main Al-Itihad headquarters of
Luq town, the volcano has exploded on a mountain au ur-ur village
of Gedo region, 380 km southwest of the capital, Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed, talking to journalists through a field radio, vhf,
today said the disaster has claimed the lives of more 290 goats
grazing near the mountain when the incident took place.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of goats and sheep were also being watered at a water
stream that runs just below the mountain at the time of the
incident.
</P>
<P>
Ahmed also said the volcano had also wounded six
herdsmen who were watering goats in a water well just near the
mountain.
</P>
<P>
According to the people who were also contacted on the
vhf radio, before the volcano has erupted they have heard a
strange noise and the whole terrain seemed to been shaking below
their feet.
</P>
<P>
According to the Bohol Garas commissioner, the volcano which
erupted two days ago has melted down the rocks and sand and spread
to the nearby terrain where the stream below the mountain and
shallow water well were also buried by the outburst of the
volcano. The surviving animals are reported to have fled the area
and many of them have been lost.
</P>
<P>
So far, no geologists or archaeologists have visited the
region to oversee what has happened there. Nor there is an
international aid agency operating in the area.
</P>
<P>
However, people in the region express concern about a possible
outburst of more volcanos in the nearby mountains.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the authorities have been telling
people to move away from the mountain sides so as to minimize the
catastrophe which might be created if more volcanoes follow.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time in the history of Somalia that a
volcano is reported. Gedo region is one of the richest in the
country in terms of the minerals and livestock.
</P>
<P>
The region is usually dry with its people having the tendency
of becoming mine workers. Currently, some of its knowledgeable
people dig some precious stones and bring them for sale in
Mogadishu and elsewhere in the neighboring countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Meets US Ambassador on Har Homa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu met with U.S. Ambassador Matin Indyk in Tel
Aviv this afternoon to discuss the controversial government
decision to build a new settlement at Har Homa in East Jerusalem,
Israel radio reported.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was arranged after the cabinet's Ministerial
Committee on Jerusalem Affairs made the decision Wednesday evening,
and Indyk relayed a message to Netanyahu from U.S. President Bill
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton Administration expressed "disappointment" Wednesday
over Israel's decision to go ahead with construction of Har
Homa settlement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told reporters
that the move "is not one that will build trust and confidence,"
which he said ought to be the cornerstone of the
Israeli-Palestinian relationship.
</P>
<P>
"Frankly, the U.S. would have preferred a different decision.
We would have preferred a different decision. We would have
preferred that this decision not have been taken," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, Burns called on the Palestinian National
Authority (PNA) not to escalate the situation, saying that threats
of violence are "the language of the past."
</P>
<P>
"The U.S. would obviously like to see calm in the occupied
territories, in Jerusalem and throughout Israel," burns
stated.
</P>
<P>
"We'd like to see a disagreement on any issue, including this
issue, resolved peacefully between the Palestinians and the
Israelis," he said. "We reject those who call for violence --
those on either side, Israelis or Palestinians."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the U.S. position, Hanan Ashrawi, PNA Minister
of Higher Education, told Israel Radio today that the U.S. should
have taken steps to prevent Israel to approve the construction of
Har Homa settlement in East Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
