<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanon Welcomes French, European Role in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Rafik
Hariri reiterated here today his country's welcome for a French
and European role in the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Milhem Karam, chairman of the Lebanese
Journalists Association, the prime minister believed that the
European role in the region will be "crystalized no matter
whether with the help of the United States or not."
</P>
<P>
The region has "entered a new stage" after U.S. President
Bill Clinton was re-elected and Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu took power, Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
"Europe is trying to play a role, and we welcome the European
role generally and the French role particularly," Hariri said.
</P>
<P>
"For this reason the Lebanese-French and Syrian-French ties
have been fastly strengthened," he added.
</P>
<P>
French Foreign Minister Herve de Charette is scheduled to
visit Israel, Syria and Lebanon next week.
</P>
<P>
Syria has already taken action, Hariri said, describing a
European trip which Syrian Vice President Abdul-Halim Khaddam
and Foreign Minister Farouq al-shara started this morning as
"useful."
</P>
<P>
Khaddam and al-shara arrived in Paris this morning and
delivered to French President Jacques Chirac a message from
Syrian President Hafez Assad.
</P>
<P>
Hariri also declared that he "sensed a good understanding of
the Lebanese position" during his visit to the Vatican and Italy
earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
The Lebanese prime minister had a meeting with Pope John Paul
in the Vatican Monday, after which Paul's spokesman announced
that the pope will visit Beirut on May 10 and 11.
</P>
<P>
Syria and Lebanon hope that a more effective European role in
the Middle East will increase the weight of their leverage in
peace negotiations with Israel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
