<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African C'Wealth Summit Ends in Botswana </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Leaders from Commonwealth's 18
African member states ended their two-day round-table summit in
Botswana's northern resort town of Kasane today, according to a
Ziana report from that city.
</P>
<P>
In a communique released at the end of the summit, the heads
of state underlined that "sustainable democracy could only grow
within societies and could neither be prescribed nor imposed from
outside."
</P>
<P>
In expressing this belief, they referred to the experience of
de-colonialization of the continent and their own national
struggles for political freedom which had been inspired by the
desire to win democratic rights for their peoples.
</P>
<P>
The roundtable summit, organized by the Commonwealth
Secretariat, reviewed progress in the democratization process in
their respective countries since the adoption of the Harare
Commonwealth Declaration of 1991.
</P>
<P>
In the period since the signing of Harare Declaration, the
Africa continent had made considerable progress in democratic
restructuring, said the leaders in the communique.
</P>
<P>
They stressed the ingredients of democracy which included the
right of people to elect freely their government, the primacy of
the rule of law and the independence of the judiciary, the right
of freedom of expression and association and the transparency and
accountability of government.
</P>
<P>
They also noted challenges and impediments in the way of
consolidating democracy, especially poverty, underdevelopment and
tribalism.
</P>
<P>
It needs national effort by all political leaders to cultivate
a culture of tolerance, mutual respect and cooperation to promote
national peace and stability in order to remove the impediments.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria was absent because its membership to the Commonwealth
was suspended at Auckland, New Zealand in 1995.
</P>
<P>
The summit was attended by the presidents or prime ministers
of Botswana, Cameroun, the Gambia, Ghana, Kenya, Lesotho, Malawi,
Mauritius, Mozambique, Namibia, Seychelles, Sierra Leone, South
Africa, Swaziland, Tanzania, Uganda, Zambia and Zimbabwe.
</P>
</TEXT>
