<HEADLINE> Turkey Expels Iranian Consul General </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Turkish Foreign Ministry today
declared Iranian Erzurum Consul General Saeed Zadeh as persona
non Grata.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Ministry said that it summoned Zadeh
today and asked him to leave Turkey within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry made the decision as Zadeh made
speeches about the tensions in the Turkish-Iranian relations to
a Turkish private news agency and some television channels
Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
Zadeh accused Deputy Chief of General Staff of Turkish Armed
Forces Cevik Bir of making remarks in Washington as
"irresponsible".
</P>
<P>
He said: "some pressure groups dispatched General Bir to
the United States and forced him to make speech."
</P>
<P>
Bir called Iran a supporter of terrorism during a joint
U.S.-Turkish Council meeting in Washington.
</P>
<P>
Iran issued a protest Monday over the remarks by Bir and
said Bir's words were irresponsible, unacceptable and similar to
those by the U.S. and Israel.
</P>
<P>
Ankara and Tehran have been in a diplomatic quarrel
following a controversial speech made by Iranian Ambassador to
Turkey Muhammad Reza Baqeri at the commemoration of "Al-quds
(Jerusalem) Night" on February 1.
</P>
<P>
Baqeri's remarks angered Turkish Foreign Ministry, which
lodged a protest note against its behavior, saying he should
not comment on Turkey's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Baqeri rejected the accusations of the Turkish government,
and left Ankara for Tehran last week, setting off reports that he
had been expelled covertly.
</P>
<P>
However, Iran denied such a report and said that Baqeri
had just returned home for consultations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
