<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chilean President Criticizes U.S. Helms-Burton Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chilean President
Eduardo Frei today criticized the U.S. Helms-Burton law as
"counter-productive" and a law of "intervention in the free rights
of a nation."
</P>
<P>
"It has been counter-productive," Frei, who was on a four-day
visit to the United States, told a National Press Club news
conference.
</P>
<P>
"I believe the Helms-Burton law is a law of intervention in the
free rights of a nation," the Chilean president said before going
to Congress to urge the U.S. lawmakers to take action to speed
negotiation of free trade with Chile.
</P>
<P>
The law enacted last March by a Republican-led Congress has
angered Europeans, Canadians, Mexicans and other U.S. allies who
accuse Washington of trying to force their hand on sanctions
against Cuba.
</P>
<P>
The Clinton administration wants to expand the North America
Free Trade Agreement, which links Canada, Mexico and the United
States, to include all other Latin American countries but Cuba.
</P>
</TEXT>
