<HEADLINE> Nyerere Urges Implementing Pact on Sino-Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Former Tanzanian
President Julius Nyerere today urged an immediate implementation
of a textile joint venture agreement between Tanzania and
China, saying the delay is costing the government dearly.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere made the call this evening during a visit of the
Urafiki Textile Mill, which, built with Chinese assistance but
mainly managed by local Tanzanians, started production in July
1968 at 95 percent production capacity for a decade before
tumbling to 15 percent in the 1980s due to mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
In order to improve the efficiency and productivity of the
mill, the governments of Tanzania and China signed a joint
venture agreement last October. Its implementation, however, was
stalled owing to a number of reasons.
</P>
<P>
Any further delay would increase the dearly cost experienced
by the Tanzanian government, noted the Tanzanian senior
statesman.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Yu Kaiming, General Manager of the Tanzania China
Friendship Textile Company (TCFTC), told Nyerere that the joint
venture could not take off because of three major snags.
</P>
<P>
The first obstacle was the tedious proceeding of some relative
laws of Tanzania which Yu said had stagnated the project.
</P>
<P>
Another stumbling block was the delay on the part of the
Tanzania government to pay more than 800 would-be retrenchees, as
had been agreed upon.
</P>
<P>
"Huge debts to Tanzania Electric Supply Company, National
Urban Water Authority and the National Provident Fund the mill
owes is another major set back," said the general manager.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere, who expressed grave concern over the progress of the
project, said the matter reflected that Tanzania need to address
a lot of problems before it enters the 21st century smoothly.
</P>
<P>
Without technical know-how, a sound infrastructure and good
governance, Tanzania would not be able to enter the new century
emphatically, noted the former president.
</P>
<P>
"Time is money and time waits for no man. Whatever decisions
made should be implemented today and never tomorrow in order to
save both time and money," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Nyerere thanked China for entering into joint-venture to bail
the crippled mill out, and challenged workers to take care of it
because the factory was like a cow which produced milk for them.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile. Tanzania's deputy minister for industries and
trade, Shamin Khan, told Nyerere while visiting the mill that
most of the bottlenecks to the implementation of the joint
venture had been dealt with.
</P>
<P>
"The main task for the new board, which will soon take over,
will be to finalize the transfer transactions, which we hope will
be smooth," she said, adding that most of the things which
delayed the implementation have been "ironed down". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
