<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-27 21:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mubarak Warns Against Israeli Settlement Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak
today called on Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu not to
take any steps relevant to Jerusalem before reaching an agreement
with the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
After giving the go-ahead for two oil wells in the northwestern
governorate of Mersa Matruth, which overlooks the Mediterranean,
Mubarak told reporters that he will soon meet with Netanyahu to
discuss the Israeli decision on a new housing project in East
Jerusalem, which has sparked widespread Palestinian demonstrations
as well as fierce criticisms from the U.S. and Arab and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government Wednesday approved plans on building
6,500 housing units for the Jewish settlers in Har Homa, a
tree-covered hill taken by Israel in the 1967 Middle East War. An
additional 3,000 homes would be built for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Instead of imposing a status quo (on East Jerusalem), Israel
should resort to negotiation and take into consideration the
public opinion before taking a decision, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
"If we do want to achieve peace, then we must solve thorny
issues by negotiation and not by imposing a fait accompli," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that he had informed Netanyahu, in a phone
conversation Wednesday, that he feared a flare-up of violence
because of Israeli new constructions plan in East Jerusalem, which
the Palestinians want to have as the capital of a Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
On his March 10 trip to Washington, Mubarak said he would
discuss with U.S. President Bill Clinton the peace process and
other pending problems, especially Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had defended the project as a move to alleviate a
shortage of housing for Arabs and Jews in the city.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians see the project as an Israeli attempt to
strengthen its hold on the holy city and preempt the peace
negotiations set for March to determine the final status of the
occupied territories, including East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
"I am afraid the situation will worsen and the peace process be
further compounded as a result of this move," the president said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Palestinian Ambassador to Egypt Zohdi
al-Qodra said today the Israeli move would "lead to overwhelming
rage among the Palestinian people." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
