<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thousands in Germany Protest against Visa Requirement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Thousands of Germans and
Foreigners today held demonstrations across Germany in protest
against a government plan to introduce visa requirements for
children from the main origin countries of Germany's immigrant
workers.
</P>
<P>
In Berlin, about 2000 people took to the street and formed a
human chain around the city's town hall.
</P>
<P>
Another human chain also surrounded the Michel church in
Hamburg while thousands of school children boycotted lessons in
response to a call from Germany's Turkish community which
described the visa requirements as "discriminating and hostile to
the family".
</P>
<P>
According to German media reports, demonstrations were also
staged in cities like Stuttgart, Kiel and Neumuester.
</P>
<P>
Under previous regulations, children under 16 years of age from
Turkey, Morocco, Tunisia and the former Yugoslavia do not need to
apply for visa when they come to visit their parents working in
Germany. They are also exempted from residential permit
requirements. But these exemptions are due to be lifted under a
decree issued by the German Interior Ministry in January.
</P>
<P>
The new regulations will only come into effect if they are
approved by April 15 by the German upper house of parliament where
the opposition Social Democratic Party (SPD) controls a majority.
The SPD reportedly is calling for changes to the decree.
</P>
<P>
The German trade union federation DGB was quoted by the German
news agency DPA as saying that the new decree was a false signal
to be sent in the European Year Against Racism. It also said that
the new regulations would work against efforts to integrate
immigrant workers' children born in the country into German
society. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
