<HEADLINE> Commercial Courts to be Set Up in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Commercial courts will
be established next July to expedite the settlement of tax
claims, implement appropriate sanctions on tax offenders and
ensure that tax arrears will be minimized.
</P>
<P>
Principal Secretary in the Ministry of Finance Peter Ngumbullu
told a high-level policy meeting between Tanzania and Japan here
today that by next June, the government will also have adopted an
action plan for increasing the tax base.
</P>
<P>
"This will include ways of taxing sectors like agriculture and
mining whose contribution to the tax effort continues to be
insignificant relative to their importance to the economy," he
said.
</P>
<P>
According to the official Daily News, the principal secretary
told the meeting at kilimajaro hotel that ways of increasing tax
compliance will also be studied, adding that preparations for the
introduction of the value added tax (VAT) scheduled for next June
will also continue.
</P>
<P>
He told the participants of the meeting which is also attended
by Japan's special assistant to the Minister for foreign Affairs
Michio Mizoguchi that there has been important improvement in tax
administration since the formation of the Tanzania Revenue
Authority (TRA).
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Minister for Finance Daniel Yona said Tanzania aims
to increase trade with Japan and attract more investment from it.
</P>
<P>
Opening the high level policy discussions between Tanzania and
Japan earlier, Yona said Tanzania is glad to note that more
Japanese private companies are investing in the country.
</P>
<P>
The finance minister told the meeting that the government is
designing aid strategies whereby external assistance will be
concentrated on a few key sectors in the economy.
</P>
<P>
He cited the priority sectors as agriculture, education,
health, water, energy, communication, transport, environment and
promotion of private sector development.
The talks will continue tomorrow. 
</P>
</TEXT>
