<HEADLINE> French Economists Optimistic about Economic Ties </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- French economists have expressed
optimism over the perspective of France's economic cooperations
with China, and have called for a more aggressive engagement in
the Chinese market, said local media reports.
</P>
<P>
"There are fantastic potentials (in the Chinese market),
especially when you go down to different regions and out of
Beijing to meet the Chinese enterprises," the daily Le Figaro
quoted an official of the Ministry of Exterior Trade of France as
saying.
</P>
<P>
The Delegate Minister for Finance and Exterior Trade of France,
Yve Galland, is presently leading a delegation of both small and
medium French business leaders and large entrepreneurs on a visit
in China to seek contracts with Chinese enterprises in Shanghai,
Tianjin and Liaoning.
</P>
<P>
The economic daily Les Echos said that although bilateral trade
between France and China has been rising since the beginning of
1990s, France now only shares 2 percent of the Chinese market, as
is compared with 17 percent by Japan, 8 percent by the United
States, and 5.5 percent by Germany.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, France's export to China stood at 12.4 billion francs
(2.4 billion U.S. dollars), while its import from China was valued
at 30 billion francs (6 billion U.S. dollars), said the daily.
</P>
<P>
French economists said that France is particularly interested
in cooperating with China in the fields of airspace industry,
agriculture and food industries, energy, insurance and financial
services.
</P>
<P>
French President Jacques Chirac will inaugurate a big
exposition gathering products from 250 major French enterprises in
Shanghai, when he pays a state visit to China in mid-May, said
local press reports.
</P>
<P>
Laure Mellerio, secretary general of the France-China Committee
of the Conseil National du Patronat Francais (CNPF), said that
French enterprises should be more engaged in China's
infrastructure construction, such as building roads, improving the
means of transport, developing telecommunication networks, and
exploiting energy products.
</P>
<P>
Le Figaro quoted other economists as saying that France could
win contracts in China's automobile equipments industry, chemical
industry, fashion accessories factories, and food industry.
</P>
<P>
The French enterprises which have been operating in China, such
as Alcatel Alstholm, Citroen, Renault, L'Air Liquide, Schneider,
Lafarge, Carrefour, Galeries Lafayette and Printemps, are also
optimistic about their future businesses in China, according to Le
Figaro.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
