<HEADLINE> Tanzania Urges Integration of Small National </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Tanzanian Minister for
Communications and Transport William Kusila today stressed the
need for small national airlines to integrate so as to survive
stiff competition in air transportation.
</P>
<P>
"It is a reality that as competition continues and grows the
small national airlines cannot survive on their own. They should
better integrate, otherwise they would finally succumb to the
situation," said the minister when opening the Royal Dutch
Airlines (KLM) and Kenya Airways joint offices here.
</P>
<P>
The minister said small national airlines could develop a
beneficial relationship with airlines of advanced countries
without perceiving themselves as juniors.
</P>
<P>
He also said they could get a successful technology transfer
and manpower development project through the integration.
</P>
<P>
"There are other arenas such as distribution, marketing,
pooling of spares, joint placement of insurance and use of
computer reservations system in which interests of the parties
may be compatible," Kusila pointed out.
</P>
<P>
"At the end of the day we cannot underate the fact that as
corporate entities with separate identities, the survivability of
each is paramount," he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Kusila expressed hopes that through their
partnership, the two airlines would make efforts to develop and
improve tourism in Tanzania, adding that the government hoped to
see a steady increase in frequencies of air services to the
country.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, KLM vice-president and African area manager, Ron
Sohipper, and Kenya Airways managing director and chief
executive, Brial Davies, promised that the two airlines would
offer better services at competitive prices.
</P>
<P>
Dar es Salaam is their first joint office in Africa Under the
partnership, which was effected last November. KLM holds 26
percent shares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
