<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researcher Says Low-fat Milk May Trigger Diabetes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- A medical researcher said on
Wednesday that he had evidence that milk and dairy products could
trigger diabetes in people predisposed to developing the disease,
said a report in today's Daily Telegraph.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Bob Elliott, a professor of Auckland Medical
School of New Zealand, as saying that he believed the cause was a
mutant protein known as beta casein A1, found in low-fat,
high-protein milk.
</P>
<P>
Addressing an international dairy conference in Palmerston in
northern New Zealand, Elliott said the findings, if further
proved, would have implications for the dairy industry worldwide,
which, in the past two decades, has switched to breeding cattle
specifically to meet consumer demand for lower-fat milk.
</P>
<P>
The professor added that the more traditional, higher-fat milk
contained a different form of protein known as A2, which was
harmless. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bearing Company Floats B-Shares on Shenzhen Exchange </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHENZHEN, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Wafangdian Bearing
Company Ltd, based in Dalian City, Liaoning Province, successfully
issued b-shares today on the Shenzhen Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
B-shares are designated only for overseas buyers.
</P>
<P>
These are the first b-shares issued by a company from the
northeast China province, the oldest industrial base in China.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, it is also the first b-share issued in the
country this year, according to official sources.
</P>
<P>
A total of 330 million shares of the new issue will be sold, at
a face value of one yuan. The company will hold 200 million
shares, 60.6 percent of the total, while 130 million shares, 39.4
percent, will be sold to overseas players.
</P>
<P>
The new issue has drawn attention from some overseas giants
such as SKF of Sweden, the largest bearing manufacturer in the
world, which has purchased 19.7 percent of the shares.
</P>
<P>
The Wafangdian Company, which is among the 100 pilot Chinese
firms authorized by the state to set up a modern enterprise
mechanism, is expected to take in over 400 million yuan through
the issuing of b-shares.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the firm made 1.658 billion yuan in sales, 246 million
yuan in pre-tax profits and 139 million in net profits. 
</P>
</TEXT>
