<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Companies Support China's National Treatment Policy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- About half of Hong Kong's
companies engaged in manufacturing and trading on the Chinese
mainland supported the policy of national treatment, according to
the Hong Kong Trade Development Council (TDC).
</P>
<P>
Another 11.3 percent said this measure was beneficial to their
investment in the mainland, a survey report of TDC shows.
</P>
<P>
The report was based on two surveys, in which a total of 990
companies were approached.
</P>
<P>
To collect the views of local businesses on China's Ninth
Five-year Plan (1996-2000), a questionnaire survey targeted at
commercial and industrial enterprises engaging in processing trade
on the mainland was conducted last October. In January 1997, a
telephone survey focusing on services companies acquainted with
China's tertiary sector was carried out.
</P>
<P>
The report noted that the liberalization of the services
sector, an important issue in the plan, was generally supported by
Hong Kong services providers. Half of those surveyed reckoned that
the move was of "great advantage" to their investment in the
mainland.
</P>
<P>
With regard to the priority development of energy,
infrastructure and high-technology projects under the plan, 10
percent of the respondents found the policy of "great" advantage
to their investment, pointing out that it both increases
investment opportunities and helps improve the investment
environment.
</P>
<P>
The report also showed that in general, Hong Kong companies
were satisfied with the investment environment "hardware" on the
mainland, but found the investment environment "software" had much
room for improvement.
</P>
<P>
As far as "hardware" was concerned, close to 80 percent of the
respondents agreed that "transportation facilities" were better
than two or three years ago, while 63 percent indicated that
"infrastructure facilities" had improved.
</P>
<P>
As for "software", 51 percent of those surveyed reckoned that
"production efficiency" had been upgraded, 62 percent pointed out
that "product quality control" had made an improvement, and 41
percent found an increase in "opportunities in the domestic
market".
</P>
<P>
With regard to areas which required urgent improvement,
"unreasonable charges" topped the list. Some 78 percent of the
respondents pointed out that the malpractice of "charging taxes
and miscellaneous fees in day-to-day operation" had become worse.
</P>
<P>
Under the present investment conditions, 49 percent of the
respondents who are engaged in trade and manufacturing still
planned to increase their investment in the mainland over the next
few years, while 87 percent of those in the services sector had
the same plans.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0073 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Qualifies for Dunhill Cup Soccer  Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China qualified for the
final of the Dunhill Cup soccer tournament with a 3-1 victory over
Zimbabwe in a semi-final here Friday evening.
</P>
<P>
China led 2-0 at half time.
</P>
<P>
The slippery pitch following the downpour here made it
difficult for both teams.
</P>
<P>
The Africans, more familiar playing in such conditions, settled
down faster and had two brilliant opportunities in the first 20
minutes.
</P>
<P>
In the 17th minute, Gilbert Mushangazhike's left-foot shot hit
the post. Three minutes later, Masimba Dinyero had a powerful
shot, but saved by Chinese goalie Ou Chuliang.
</P>
<P>
However, the Chinese eleven made up for several earlier misses
when it netted two goals in seven minutes. At the 22nd minute into
the game, Fan Zhiyi, receiving a pass from Peng Weiguo, opened the
scoring with a header.
</P>
<P>
Seven minutes later, Li Ming tapped in a cross from Hao Haidong
for a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
Just two minutes into the second half, the match was halted for
20 minutes when the lights at the stadium went off.
</P>
<P>
The delay due to the blackout did not affect China's rhythm in
the second half as it maintained its pressure on the Africans.
</P>
<P>
China sealed the match with the third goal in the 58th minute
through Fan Zhiyi who again headed in Peng Wei Guo's freekick from
outside the penalty box.
</P>
<P>
Zimbabwe got a consolation goal just two minutes before the
long whistle through substitute Morgan Nkathazo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
