<HEADLINE> India's New Budget for 1997-98 Doubles Fund for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The United Front government
places priority on science and technology in the new budget for
1997-98 which doubles its allocation fund over the previous fiscal
year, Finance Minister P. Chidambaram said today.
</P>
<P>
Chidambaram, who presented the budget to parliament this
evening, proposed to increase three billion rupees (84.51 million
US dollars) for the country's science and technology sector.
</P>
<P>
The scheme to match every commercial rupee earned by national
laboratories and Indian institutes of technology with an equal
amount of government money, introduced last year, will continue on
a permanent basis, providing additional revenues for science and
technology.
</P>
<P>
The budgetary outlay for defense will be 356.2 billion rupees
(10.03 billion US dollars), up by 66 billion rupees (1.86 billion
US dollars) over the 1996-97 budget allocation.
</P>
<P>
A new bill would be introduced to deal strongly with money
laundering. A new policy would be formulated for exploration in
oil and gas in the country and new incentives for investment by
foreign investors and non-resident Indians would be also
introduced, the finance minister said.
</P>
<P>
About 75 billion rupees (2.11 billion US dollars) are being
earmarked for food grains and sugar subsidies in the new budget,
an increase of 14.34 billion rupees (403.94 million US dollars)
over last year. Subsidy on locally made fertilizers will rise to
52.4 billion rupees (1.48 billion US dollars) from 47.43 billion
rupees (1.34 billion US dollars) for 1996-97.
</P>
<P>
Total expenditure is estimated at 2.325 trillion rupees (65.488
billion US dollars) while total receipts at existing rates of
taxation are estimated at 2.319 trillion rupees (65.32 billion US
dollars) for 1997-98. The balance of 1.696 trillion rupees (47.78
billion US dollars) is for non-plan expenditure, the finance
minister said.
</P>
<P>
Net external assistance is expected to be 24.35 billion rupees
(685.92 million US dollars) for 1997-98, he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0076 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Issue 500,000-Ruble Bank Note </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Russia is to issue a 500,000-
ruble (about 88 U.S. dollars at current rate) bank note - its
largest ever - next week, an official said today.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Chairman of the Central Bank Arnold Voilukov told
reporters that the decision to introduce the new note is linked
to an increase in the average monthly salary, which is expected to
reach 1.15 million rubles (202 dollars) in April, 1997.
</P>
<P>
The new note, featuring pictures of the Monument to Peter the
Great and the Arkhangelsk city in northern Russia, has better
protection against counterfeiting, Voilukov said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the note would have a special dye that changes
color depending on the angle of viewing, among 22 devices designed
to make it more counterfeiting-proof. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
