<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emotions Prevail Over Rational Senses: Study </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Emotions often prevail over
rational senses when a person is faced with difficult decisions,
an American study showed.
</P>
<P>
Scientists in the United States found that unconscious
emotional signals - intuition or a "hunch" - take part in
decision-making well before conscious thoughts do, the journal
Science reported today.
</P>
<P>
A research team of the University of Iowa College of Medicine,
Iowa City, made the conclusion after studying patients who find
difficulty making up their minds when faced with risks.
</P>
<P>
Comparing the gambling ability of a group of brain-damaged
patients with that of normal individuals, they found that people
rely on a range of emotional cues when making decisions.
</P>
<P>
The discovery fits in with previous experiment results.
Psychologists already find that when people face tricky decisions,
such as choosing their spouses or buying new cars, they usually
draw on more than just rational thought and let feelings get their
own way in the process of decision-making. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
