<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Nuclear Waste Transport Began Amid Strong Protest </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Germany's rail transport of
nuclear waste began today amid strong anti-nuclear protests, under
the protection of the country's biggest police operation since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
The first of a total of six containers carrying highly
radio active nuclear waste left Bavaria's Gundremmingen power
station for Walheim in neighboring Baden-Wuerttemberg state, where
it will join three others from Germany and two from France in the
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
The special train shipping the spent nuclear fuel rods is due
to reach a temporary underground storage depot at Gorleben in
Germany's northern state of Lower-Saxony on March 2.
</P>
<P>
Police have detained about 100 people trying to block heavy
lorries carrying the three containers from the nuclear power
station in Baden-Wuerttemberg, where the train from Bavaria was
stranded for about 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
Security cost for the transport is estimated around 100 million
marks (60 million U.S. dollars), compared to 46 million marks for
the last such transport.
</P>
<P>
Thirty thousand police officers are mobilized for shielding the
shipment. Supported by crack federal border troops, they are
heavily armed and will be deploying armored personnel carriers,
helicopters and water cannons.
</P>
<P>
Last year's Gorleben trip led to massive demonstrations, mostly
peaceful. However police used water cannons to clear people
blocking railway lines and there were attacks on police by masked
left-wing extremists who hurled stones.
</P>
<P>
The high security cost is part of the anti-nuclear lobby's
strategy trying to drive the price of nuclear power through the
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
In the recent protest over this year's nuclear transport,
anti-nuclear activists allegedly sabotaged overhead power lines
for electric trains and railway signal facilities to disrupt rail
services.
</P>
<P>
Violent protest has also fueled heated debate in parliament.
Government parties accused the Greens Party of encouraging people
against the rule of law and as a result to undermine democracy.
</P>
<P>
The Greens and the Party of Democratic Socialism (PSD) want a
ban on nuclear waste transport and have supported the recent mass
protest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
