<HEADLINE> Qiao Shi: Supervision Is Welcome (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese senior Party leader
Qiao Shi said here today that the Communist Party of China (CPC)
sincerely welcomes supervision from the non-Communist parties, and
urged Party officials at all levels to pay close attention to and
modestly accept suggestions and criticisms from the non-Communist
parties.
</P>
<P>
Qiao, a member of the Standing Committee of the CPC Central
Committee's Political Bureau, this afternoon paid a visit to
members of the Eighth National Committee of the Chinese People's
Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC), which started its fifth
annual session Thursday in Beijing, and joined them in a group
discussion.
</P>
<P>
After listening to several CPPCC National Committee members
from various non-Communist parties, who focused on the
achievements of the CPPCC and its future development, Qiao said
that he was very glad to have the opportunity to join the
discussion and hear the members' opinions.
</P>
<P>
"You have just put forth some great ideas and proposals that
are very inspiring, and some problems you mentioned really deserve
close attention and should be addressed in practical work," he
noted.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the multi-party cooperation and political
consultation system under the CPC leadership, Qiao stressed that
it is of critical importance for China's development that the
CPC and the non-Communist parties preserve a relationship of
long-term co-existence and mutual supervision.
</P>
<P>
"During the period of democratic revolution and since the
founding of New China in 1949, especially since the reform and
opening up began in 1978, the CPC has had close cooperation with
the non-Communist parties, and will continue to do so in future,"
he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
