<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Holds Talks with Beninese FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and
Foreign Minister Qian Qichen expressed satisfaction over the
smooth development of bilateral relations between China and Benin
here today.
</P>
<P>
Since the two countries restored their diplomatic relations in
1972, friendly co-operation in various sectors have been fruitful
and exchanges of high-level visits have been frequent, which have
deepened the mutual understanding and trust between the two
nations, Qian noted, during talks with visiting Beninese Foreign
Minister Pierre Osho.
</P>
<P>
Osho, on behalf of President Mathieu Kerekou and Benin's
government and people, first expressed condolences over the death
of Chinese leader Deng Xiaoping, lauding him as a "great friend"
of the people of Benin.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed his gratitude, and said that China will
steadfastly stride along the road of building socialism with
Chinese characteristics, which was initiated by Deng, the
architect of China's modernization drive and the reform and
opening up policy.
</P>
<P>
Qian expressed appreciation over the long-term close
co-operation and mutual support between China and Benin in
international affairs. He also thanked the Beninese government for
sticking to its "one China" policy and not having any official
relations with Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
China emphasizes the development of economic and trade
relations with Benin, Qian said, and the two countries have reaped
satisfactory results through co-operation in various forms. China
is willing to actively explore new fields and channels of
cooperation together with Benin, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Osho said that although the two countries are far apart
geographically, the two peoples are emotionally close, and Benin
is proud to have such a great friend as China.
</P>
<P>
President Kerekou and the Beninese government attach great
importance to the development of bilateral relations, Osho said,
and Benin, grateful to China for its long-term support, is willing
to continue its co-operation with China in different spheres.
</P>
<P>
After the talks the two sides exchanged letters on the
continued existence of an honorary consulate of Benin in Hong Kong
after China resumes its exercise of sovereignty over the territory.
</P>
<P>
The two foreign ministers also signed an agreement on the
mutual exemption of visas between Benin and the future Hong Kong
Special Administrative Region. 
</P>
</TEXT>
