<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kinkel Proposes to Ease Russian Concern Over NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, February 28 -- German Foreign Minister Klaus Kinkel today
floated the idea to limit the stationing of conventional weapon
systems in east European candidate countries in a bid to ease
Russia's concerns over the NATO eastward expansion.
</P>
<P>
Kinkel said in a speech to the German parliament that Russian
Foreign Minister Yevgeny Primakov had told him of Moscow's concern
that NATO's military machine would advance on the Russian border.
</P>
<P>
"We can and must clear away these Russian concerns," he said.
</P>
<P>
A solution would be to limit deployment of foreign weapons in
the candidate states to a certain percent of territorial limits
agreed under an amended Treaty on Conventional Force in Europe,
Kinkel said.
</P>
<P>
He added that such limits could be monitored through an
improved system of military inspection and exchange of information.
</P>
<P>
At its Madrid summit last July, NATO is expected to select
candidates from east European countries with which it will begin
membership negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Russia at present still remains strongly against the NATO
expansion plan. It has demanded a legal-binding document on its
relations with NATO. The latter, however, only wants a charter
which does not need the approval of member states' parliaments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
