<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Foreign Exchange Reserves Doubled: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's foreign exchange
reserves have doubled to 1.08 billion U.S. dollars in the last few
days, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif said today.
</P>
<P>
The rapid increase in the foreign exchange reserves was due to
tremendous responses by Pakistanis at home and abroad to his call
for donations, Sharif said while addressing a meeting in Lahore,
the capital city of Punjab Province.
</P>
<P>
People from all over the country and abroad have been
participating with devotion, enthusiasm and determination in the
debt repayment program, he said.
</P>
<P>
He hoped that with the massive participation of the people in
the improvement of foreign exchange reserves, Pakistan would be
able to divert huge amounts for the development projects.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the devotion and dedication of the people, there was
no need to beg for loans from any international agency, he said.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped that Pakistan would be able to stand on its own
feet very soon.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's foreign debt stood at around 30 billion dollars
while its foreign exchange reserves had been left no more than 600
million dollars when Sharif was sworn in on February 17 as new
prime minister.
</P>
<P>
Sharif appealed last Sunday in his first televised speech to
both resident and overseas Pakistanis to come forward and help him
overcome the country's economic crisis.  
</P>
</TEXT>
