<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Casts Doubt on 1997 Budget, Calls for Military Reforms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
said Friday that he doubts that the 1997 federal budget targets
can be met and called for "real and profound" reforms in the
military.
</P>
<P>
In a radio address to the nation, Yeltsin said he was very
reluctant to sign the law on the 1997 budget on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"It is very doubtful the budget can be fulfilled," Yeltsin
said, "because the government has not done enough about it, and
has included unrealistic elements in it."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the amendments on the budget put forward by the
State Duma (lower house of parliament) was dominated by "populism
and lobbies" that had even worsened the budget.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin explained that he had signed the budget "because
rejecting it would mean aggravating the political situation in
Russia, and a new wave of instability would hit the least
protected citizens the hardest."
</P>
<P>
But he said he would exercise more careful control over the
drafting of the budget for next year.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the military, Yeltsin criticized the phenomenon of
officers stealing properties, and veteran soldiers bullying new
ones.
</P>
<P>
Calling for "real and profound military reforms" and reduction
of the armed forces, he pointed out that the necessity was to make
the military meet the needs of today and future, and adapt to the
changing international situation and domestic reforms.
</P>
<P>
The main task is to enhance the quality of the military, and
facilitate its professionalization process in the long run,
Yeltsin said.
</P>
<P>
Recently Defense Minister Igor Rodionov has been campaigning
for more funding for the army, saying reforms are impossible
without additional money.
</P>
<P>
Rebuking him on Wednesday, Yeltsin said the minister should
stop "whining" and get down to the task of reforming the army.
</P>
</TEXT>
