<HEADLINE> Tory Loses Parliamentary Majority After Key By-election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Britain's ruling Conservative
Party lost parliamentary majority after losing a key by-election
in Wirral South in northwestern England, putting Labor leader Tony
Blair in a stronger position for a general election.
</P>
<P>
The Labor victory, timed just weeks before the general
election, reduced the chances of a triumph by Prime Minister John
Major in the general elections which must be held by May.
</P>
<P>
On an unusually high turnout for a by-election of 73 percent,
Labor candidate Ben Chapman received 22,767 votes in Wirral South,
7,888 votes more than the 14,879 of his Conservative rival Les
Byrom.
</P>
<P>
"The public are totally disenchanted with the present
government," said Chapman, who took the place of the late Tory MP,
Barry Porter, in Wirral South.
</P>
<P>
The Conservatives won Wirral South by 8,183 votes in last
general election.
</P>
<P>
Immediately knowing the result, a Labor spokesman said: "No
party has ever lost a by-election so close to a general election,
in a seat they had won at the previous general election, and gone
on to win the general election."
</P>
<P>
The crushing victory of Labor, with 17 percent swing, reflected
the party's 20 percent lead in popularity in national opinion
polls.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the result, Labor's deputy leader John Prescott
said: "The people of Wirral South have rejected the Tories'
negative campaign and backed new Labor's positive pledges on
education, health, crime, jobs and taxes."
</P>
<P>
However, the defeated Byrom was not disheartened.
</P>
<P>
"I intend to be back in the general election in a very few
weeks time. I believe Britain's future is with John Major and we
will win the general election," he said.
</P>
<P>
Observers believe that Labor's gain of the Tories' 126th most
marginal seat will hammer government morale and bolster Labor
hopes of an outright majority in the coming general election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
