<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey Concerned About Israeli Housing project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey was concerned about
the Israeli government's decision to build new Jewish settlements
in east Jerusalem, a Turkish Foreign Ministry statement said
today.
</P>
<P>
"While the tragic events occurred in Autumn with the opening
of the archeological tunnel passing beneath of the Al Aqsa Mosque
have not been forgotten and the status of Jerusalem and the final
negotiations are expected to start soon, the project for the new
Jewish settlements announced recently has caused worries about
the success of the Middle East peace process," said the statement.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that Israel should reconsider its policy
on the building of the new Jewish settlements in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Turkey expressed the hope that all the sides concerned should
make constructive contributions to a lasting, comprehensive and
just peace and stability in the region, it added.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs approved
Wednesday the construction of 6,500 housing units in Har Homa of
east Jerusalem. The committee also allowed another 3,015 homes to
be built for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli government's action to open an archaeological
tunnel entrance next to Muslim holy sites last September set off
three days of riots which killed more than 70 people, most of them
Palestinians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
