<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Slovenia's Parliament Approves New Coalition Government </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Slovenia's parliament today
approved by a slender majority Prime Minister Janez Drnovsek's new
coalition government, ending a three-month-old crisis following
the country's November general elections last year.
</P>
<P>
The coalition government of the ex-ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDS) and ex-opposition Slovenia National Party (SLS) is
Slovenia's fourth government after its independence from former
Yugoslavia in 1991.
</P>
<P>
The LDS and the SLS shared 16 of the 17 ministerial posts in
the new government, with the last one going to the Democratic
Pensioner's Party.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the SLS Marjan Podobnik was named deputy prime
minister to be in charge of coordinations among ministries, while
former Foreign Minister Zoran Thaler retained his post.
</P>
<P>
Slovenia, a country of two million people lying between
Austria, Croatia and Italy, has been without a government since
elections on November 10, 1996, because no party won an absolute
majority.
</P>
<P>
Drnovsek, head of the LDS, failed in his first attempt to form
a government when his proposed ministerial list was rejected by
the parliament on February 6. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
