<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Vice-Premier Meets French Trade Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Chinese government takes a
positive attitude toward the trade and economic cooperation with
France, Chinese Vice-Premier Li Lanqing said here today.
</P>
<P>
During a meeting with Yves Galland, minister-delegate to
France's Ministry of Economics and Finance, Li said China is
"optimistic" about the growth of the trade and economic
cooperation between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Galland, the purpose of his trip is to expand
high-level political and economic ties between France and China,
and to prepare for the China visit of French President Jacques
Chirac in May.
</P>
<P>
Galland said he believes Chirac's visit will be a successful
one and will become a landmark in bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
France hopes that the two countries will develop sound
cooperative ties in aviation, energy, insurance and banking with
China, and that their small and medium-sized enterprises will
conduct sustainable exchanges, the Galland noted.
</P>
<P>
Li said the Chinese side is now making preparations for
Chirac's visit. He said that he believes the visit will have
historic significance and will push forward the friendly
cooperation between China and France.
</P>
<P>
Li noted that the economies of the two countries have their own
advantages and are complementary to each other.
</P>
<P>
He said that through joint efforts the trade and economic
cooperation between the two countries will grow on a solid basis,
and that the cooperation between small and medium-sized
enterprises of the two countries has good prospects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
