<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Deposits, Loans Increase in January </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Total deposits in Hong Kong
rose by 1.4 percent in January 1997, reversing the fall of 1.1
percent in December 1996, according to the statistics released by
the Hong Kong Monetary Authority (HKMA) here today.
</P>
<P>
The increase resulted from increases in both HK dollar and
foreign currency deposits of 2.2 and 0.3 percent respectively.
</P>
<P>
An HKMA spokesman said that total loans and advances rose
slightly by 0.1 percent in January, following a fall of 0.2
percent in December 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that domestic credit rose by 3.8 percent, contributed
by a 0.2 percent increase in loans for trade financing and a 4.2
percent increase in other loans for use in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Analyzed by currency, HK dollar loans rose by five percent while
foreign currency loans fell by 2.7 percent during the month. As
the increase in HK dollar loans was larger than that of HK dollar
deposits, the HK dollar loan-to-deposit ratio rose to 106.1
percent at the end of January 1997 from 103.3 percent at the end
of December 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
