<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu to Visit Cairo Next Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin
Netanyahu will visit Egypt Tuesday to discuss with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak the future of the Mideast peace process,
the Egyptian MENA news agency reported today.
</P>
<P>
Their talks will deal with the peace prospects in the region
in the light of the worsening conditions due to the recent
Israeli decision to build new Jewish settlements in east
Jerusalem which has sparked fear of flare-ups of violence.
</P>
<P>
It will be Netanyahu's first tour to Egypt since he visited the
country last June after taking office.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian president said Thursday he will discuss with
Netanyahu the Israeli decision on the new housing project in east
Jerusalem, which has ignited Palestinian demonstrations as well
as fierce criticism from the United States, Arab and European
countries.
</P>
<P>
Israel's Ministerial Committee on Jerusalem Affairs Wednesday
approved the construction of 6,500 housing units for the Jewish
settlers in Har Homa of east Jerusalem, an area taken by Israel in
the 1967 Mideast War. The committee also allowed another 3,015
homes to be built for Arabs.
</P>
<P>
Instead of imposing a status quo (on East Jerusalem), Israel
should resort to negotiations and take into consideration of the
public opinion before taking a decision, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu had defended the project as a move to alleviate a
housing shortage for the Jews and Arabs in the city.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak said that he informed Netanyahu over a phone call
Wednesday of his fear of a flare-up of violence because of the
Israeli construction plan in east Jerusalem, which the
Palestinians want it as the capital of a future Palestinian
state.
</P>
<P>
The Mubarak-Netanyahu meeting comes before Mubarak's March 10
trip to Washington, which would deal with the Mideast peace and
other pending problems, especially Jerusalem. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
