<HEADLINE> Norway Wins Men's Relay in Nordic Skiing Worlds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Norway dominated the men's
cross-country skiing with an easy win in the 4x10km relay at the
Nordic skiing world championships in Trondheim, Norway on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegian foursome Sture Sivertsen, Erling Jevne, Bjorn
Daehlie and Thomas Alsgaard left their rivals way behind to clock
a winning time of one hour 37 minutes 06.10 seconds.
</P>
<P>
Finland came second two minutes 11.20 seconds back and Italy
third 2:50.80 behind Norway, according to provisional results.
</P>
<P>
The Norwegians, who led from start to finish to the roars of a
huge crowd, were already 24 seconds clear of the Finns after the
first two legs when Daehlie set off.
</P>
<P>
Daehlie, the winner of two golds already in the 10-day
festival, increased their lead to one minute and 43 seconds.
</P>
<P>
The last two laps were a formality for Alsgaard, who took
plenty of time to pick up a Norwegian flag in the finish straight
and wave it until the line.
</P>
<P>
Finn Jari Isometsae was a distant second and Falvio Valbusia
outsprinted Russian Alexei Prokurorov to give third place to
Italy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
