<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Baseball, Soccer Players to Be Investigated for Tax Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Japanese tax authorities raided
the office and home of a business consultant on suspicion of
helping dozens of professional baseball and soccer players evade
income taxes, local reports said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The authorities also questioned some of the players who are
suspected of evading taxes under the instruction of the
consultant, based in the central Japan city of Nagoya.
</P>
<P>
The baseball players suspected of being involved are from 10 of
Japan's 12 professional teams, reports said.
</P>
<P>
Most of those suspected of improperly reporting their income
are star players who earn about 100 million yen (830,000
U.S. dollars) a year, and rookies who landed fat contracts when
they joined, the Asahi Shimbun reported.
</P>
<P>
Professional sport players are classified as self-employed, and
can claim as tax deductions money spent on equipment, commuting
and other goods and services considered necessary to their
profession.
</P>
<P>
The Asahi said the consultant, who was not identified,
allegedly had players falsely report they made payments ranging
from 10 million to 50 million yen to him for consultations, so
they could avoid paying tax on that money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
