<HEADLINE> Australian PM Asks Unemployed to Be Patient </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Australian Prime Minister
John Howard today asked the unemployed and small businesses to be
patient and wait for the federal government's economic policy to
take full effect.
</P>
<P>
Howard said over ABC Radio (Australian Broadcasting
Corporation) that the government's industrial relations reforms
would help tackle the problem of unemployment, but the laws did
not come into full effect until mid-March.
</P>
<P>
However, the prime minister refused to set a target for the
unemployment rate, which is as high as 8.6 percent now, by the
next election, saying "I am aiming to get it down as soon as
possible without any particular reference to the next election."
</P>
<P>
"We have to say, give a bit more time for those changes to
work. I promise the public that we're devoting all of our
energies. We're trying a whole lot of strategies to tackle the
problem of unemployment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that he was not surprised at criticism from small
business, but the changes to capital gains tax and industrial
relations laws would help small business.
</P>
<P>
"Can I say to them, I understand your concerns. I know why you
are still unhappy. You have reason to be unhappy, but please be a
little patient," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
