<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong, Japan Sign Air Services Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong-Japan Air
Services Agreement was formally signed here today to ensure the
smooth continuation of the air services between Hong Kong and
Japan after June 30 this year.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed by Stephen Ip, secretary for economic
services, and Hideaki Ueda, Japanese consul-general in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Mike Arnold, Hong Kong government's chief air services
negotiator, said that the text of the agreement took eight years
to negotiate. It was concluded and initialed in December 1995, and
the Sino-British Joint Liaison Group gave its endorsement in
December 1996.
</P>
<P>
He said that since the initialing of the agreement, detailed
discussions have taken place in both Hong Kong and Tokyo to
finalize the air traffic arrangements that will operate under the
new agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said that the new arrangements were finally concluded on
Wednesday after two days of talks in Hong Kong with Norifumi Ide
of the Japanese Ministry of Transport.
</P>
<P>
Representatives of Hong Kong's three airlines Cathay Pacific,
Dragonair and Air Hong Kong, and the major Japanese airlines
including All Nippon Airways, Japan Air System and Nippon Cargo
Airlines, as well as the Japanese Consul General's Office were
also present during the final round of talks.
</P>
<P>
Japan is a major market for Hong Kong's airlines. In 1996, the
Japanese market represented about 18 percent of the total revenue
earned by the airlines.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the airlines of Japan and Hong Kong together carry
some 4 million passengers each year, serving nine cities in Japan.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong-Japan Agreement is the 16th air services
agreement signed by Hong Kong. The others were signed with the
Netherlands, Switzerland, Canada, Brunei, France, New Zealand,
Malaysia, Brazil, Sri Lanka, Australia, Germany, South Korea,
Singapore, Italy and India. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
