<HEADLINE> Pak Army Called Out to Help Quake Victims </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Army troops today
have been called out in Quetta city to carry out earthquake rescue
operations along with the civil administration.
</P>
<P>
The troops including paramedical and engineering staff were
called out on the request of civil administration of Balochistan
to rescue the quake victims.
</P>
<P>
Pakistani Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif earlier ordered the
Balochistan authorities to take all possible measures to reduce
the losses of the natural disaster.
</P>
<P>
An earthquake measuring between 6.3 and 7.3 on the Richter
scale, which took place at 2:10 a.m. today, jolted Quetta valley
and other parts of northern Balochistan province for over one
minute while after-shocks of the similar intensity again shook the
valley fifteen minutes later.
</P>
<P>
The toll of the earthquake has risen to 37 while the figure of
injured has crossed 60.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities at Quetta, capital city of Balochistan,
have started relief operations in affected areas.
</P>
<P>
Emergency was declared in Quetta and police mobiles started
patrolling city areas immediately after the shocks.  
</P>
</TEXT>
