<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0133 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quetta: Pakistan's City of Earthquakes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The strong earthquake which
rocked Quetta, the capital city of Balochistan province, early
today was one of the worst in 62 years.
</P>
<P>
At least 37 people have been killed and 60 injured after an
earthquake measuring between 6.3-7.3 on the Richter scale hit
Balochistan around 2:10 a.m.
</P>
<P>
According to officials of the Pakistan Meteorological, the
epicenter of the earthquake was 140 kilometers east of Quetta and
it was felt in most of Balochistan and some parts of Sindh
province.
</P>
<P>
Quetta has a long history of earthquakes.
</P>
<P>
The first major earthquake rocked Quetta in 1935 in which some
30,000 people were killed. It measured 7.5 on the Richter scale
(R.s.).
</P>
<P>
The second was felt in 1955, with a magnitude of 6.0 on R.S.
Then again in 1974, Quetta was hit with an earthquake measuring
6.0 on R.S. and in 1975 the city was shaken with jolts measuring
5.5 on R.S.
</P>
<P>
In 1981 and 1984 tremors jolted Quetta with intensity of 6.1,
and in 1985 with of 6.6 on the R.S.
</P>
<P>
Quetta has been hit by earthquakes for the third time in the
1990s. It has already experienced an earthquake measuring 6.8 on
the R.S. in 1991 and 5.5 on R.S. in 1992.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0134 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nigerian Official on Environment Situation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Some 15,000 industrial
enterprises in Nigeria are daily polluting the country's
environment, an environment official has said.
</P>
<P>
Adegoke Adegoroye, Acting Director-General of the Federal
Environmental Protection Agency, made the disclosure in his paper
titled "Nigerian environment, current policies and direction",
which he delivered at a recent seminar in Abuja, capital of
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that of the 15,000 enterprises, only 5,000
are registered, while the rest 10,000 are operating illegally
within residential premises in cities like Lagos, Kaduna, Kano,
Port Harcourt, Onitsha and Aba.
</P>
<P>
The official pointed out that waste products from textiles,
tannery and paints industries in some cities are discharged
directly into open drainages and river channels.
</P>
<P>
In parts of Lagos, Kano, Enugu and Port Harcourt, smoke from
factories often blocks sunlight for hours and reduces visibility
to less than 20 meters, he said.
</P>
<P>
Adegoroye estimated that at least 20 million gallons of waste
oil is discharged from mechanic workshops, industries, power
stations and commercial houses on a daily basis, thereby
contaminating the land and underground waters.
</P>
<P>
He also commended the federal government's efforts at
combating environment pollutions, including the setting aside of
two percent of the country's annual revenue for environment
protection.
</P>
<P>
The government has also make it compulsory for every new and
major project to carry out a feasibility study to determine its
impact on environment, the official added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
