<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkey, Iran Suffer Setback in Bilateral </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Turkey and Iran are suffering
setbacks in their bilateral relations as Ankara expelled a
senior Iranian diplomat Thursday and Iran may expel Turkish
diplomats in retaliation.
</P>
<P>
A statement issued by the Turkish Foreign Ministry said that
it had summoned Saeede Zadeh, Iranian consul general in Erzurum,
eastern city of Turkey, declared him as persona non grata and
requested him to leave the country within 48 hours.
</P>
<P>
Turkey's decision has shown that tensions between Ankara and
Tehran are rising.
</P>
<P>
The Turkish Foreign Ministry made the tough decision after
Zadeh, through a Turkish private news agency and some television
channels Wednesday, accused Turkish Deputy Chief of General Staff
Cevik Bir of making unfriendly speeches against Iran in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Bir called Iran a supporter of terrorism during a joint
U.S.-Turkish Council meeting in the United States.
</P>
<P>
Iran issued a protest Monday, saying that what Bir said was
irresponsible, unacceptable and similar to those by the U.S. and
Israel.
</P>
<P>
Turkish official sources said that Iran may expel Turkish
Ambassador to Tehran Osman Koruturk and Consul General in Orumieh
Ufuk Ozsancak in retaliation to Turkey's attitude toward Iran.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
