<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peace Monitoring in N. Iraq Urged to Start </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Amid increasing tension in
northern Iraq, western diplomats here have called for an urgent
deployment of the Peace Monitoring Force (PMF) along the
cease-fire line to prevent any possible armed clash.
</P>
<P>
Local newspaper Daily News today quoted the sources as
saying that the PMF, which is in Turkey now, will be provided
with necessary equipment, including radio and vehicles, to carry
out its mission.
</P>
<P>
This move came following a recent statement issued by the
Patriotic Union of Kurdistan (PUK), claiming that the Iraqi
government troops and the Kurdistan Democratic Party (KDP) troops
led by Massoud Barzani are preparing for a new offensive.
</P>
<P>
The statement called on the international community,
especially the United States, Britain and Turkey, to prevent
"another onslaught by the combined Saddam-Barzani forces."
</P>
<P>
The PUK and KDP are both rival Iraqi Kurdish armed groups and
have been fighting each other for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
Northern Iraq has been controlled by Kurdish rebels since the
1991 gulf war, but it split into rival zones in the PUK-KDP
conflict in 1994.
</P>
<P>
A glimmer of hope was expected for one time when the PUK and
KDP signed a peace deal on October 31, 1996 under the mediation
of the United States, Britain and Turkey.
</P>
<P>
According to the accord, both groups agreed to withdraw
their troops from the disputed areas along the cease-fire line
and take all necessary measures to provide security for the
members of the planned PMF.
</P>
<P>
The Iraq-backed KDP launched an attack on the Iran-backed PUK
in August last year and captured most of the northern part of
Iraq, which led to U.S. air strike against Iraqi military
targets.



28/02/97 11:16 GMT

=02281020
NNNN
18:20 18:20 g # PAB
</P>
</TEXT>
