<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Flood-stricken North China Province Starts Spring Planting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- North China's Hebei
Province has started planting after having repaired reservoirs
and rivers that suffered damage during the province's
worst flood in 50 years last year.
</P>
<P>
It has spent over 1.27 billion yuan on water resources work to
improve its ability to resist floods, since last autumn, and
nearly 10,000 technicians have been sent to the fields to assist
farmers in improving their farming.
</P>
<P>
Preparations have also been reported from northeast China's
Liaoning Province to the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region in the
northwest, where it is colder.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning, which has more than 150,000 tractors, has offered
subsidies for farmers who buy tractors this year, to encourage
greater use of agricultural machinery.
</P>
<P>
Xinjiang has bought over two million tons of fertilizer and
4,000 tons of pesticides from China and abroad, and trucks and
trains carrying these materials move back and forth across the
region, amid continued snow and chilly weather.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
