<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Southwest Chinese Province Cracks Down On Inferior Goods </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The government of China's
Sichuan Province has limited the production of 80 kinds of
technologically inferior products in a bid to improve the quality
of its products.
</P>
<P>
The prohibited products were those causing pollution, or which
had a low material recovery rate, or which did not meet government
standards.
</P>
<P>
Included were products from 16 plants that manufacture clay
bricks made with earth from farmland, glass plants with an annual
production capacity of fewer than 500,000 cases, small paper
mills, rare earth separating plants, and coke and pesticide makers
with improper methods.
</P>
<P>
The province has also placed restrictions on products that
consume a lot of energy, but are interior in quality, or don't
sell well. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
