<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 10:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netanyahu Meets With Turkish Army Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Israel was seeking common
ground against "extremist elements" with Turkey, by using the
opportunity of the visit by the Turkish army chief, according to
a report of the state-run Israel Radio today.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Prime Minister Binyamin Netanyahu met here Thursday
with Turkish Chief of Staff General Ismail Karadayi who is on his
first visit to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
"We appreciate Turkey and its army and I believe our
cooperation is a very important component in securing the
aspiration for peace and stability in the Middle East, an area
that has many extremist elements," said a statement issued by the
Prime Minister's Office Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of "extremist elements," Netanyahu did not say whom
he referred to, according to the statement. But observers here
believe Turkish separatists are included.
</P>
<P>
"Turkey and Israel have a joint interest in securing
stability, peace and moderation in our region," the statement
quoted Netanyahu as saying.
</P>
<P>
In response, Karadayi said the relations between Turkey and
Israel "have always been good and will be even better in the
future."
</P>
<P>
He said that "there are excellent relations between our
armies and our military industries and this visit left me with a
very good impression."
</P>
<P>
Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai also met with
Karadayi during his three-day visit at the invitation of Chief
of General Staff Lt.-Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak.
</P>
<P>
Karadayi's visit to Israel came a year after a tour by his
deputy, General Cevik Bir, who signed an agreement to hold joint
maneuvers and training exercises with the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israeli pilots have subsequently been allowed to use Turkish
airspace for training, and Israel Aircraft Industries is to
upgrade 54 Turkish F-4 fighters in a deal worth 640 million
U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Israel attaches great importance to strengthening its ties
with Turkey, an Islamic nation in the region and also a member
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO).
</P>
<P>
Turkey has been fighting a bitter war against Kurdish
separatists of the Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK). But Israel is
very careful not to get openly involved in the Turkish internal
affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
