<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cooperating With Rest of World in Nature Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China has taken a big step
forward in cooperating with other countries in protecting nature,
according to Wang Zhibao, vice-minister of Forestry, who said that
joint efforts have been made with other countries like Japan,
Australia, and the US.
</P>
<P>
He noted that during the past decade China has signed six
international conventions on global climatic changes,
anti-desertification work, and protection of wildlife, wetlands,
bio-diversity, and marine resources.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, the joint efforts between China and Japan
for protecting the crested ibis have proven to be most successful,
with the numbers of this famous rare bird increasing nearly
ten-fold.
</P>
<P>
He said that the Ministry of Forestry, the main authority in
natural protection in China, has also achieved some good results
in protecting the giant panda and rain-forests through
international cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"During the past several years we have held several
international symposiums on protection of nature and have
established close relations with international counterparts," Wang
added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
