<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 56 Die in Fight for Pasture Between Kenyans, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- More than 50 raiders of
Uganda and six herdsmen of Kenya were killed on Tuesday evening
during fighting for grazing rights inside Uganda, the Daily
Nation reported today.
</P>
<P>
The paper said that the Kenyan General Service Unit and the
Administration Police had deployed forces at the border to
preserve peace following the incident.
</P>
<P>
The herdsmen in West Pokot District of Kenya had trekked to
the Chekarani area of Uganda to graze their animals in
accordance with an agreement between Ugandan and Kenyan
administrators, the paper noted.
</P>
<P>
The agreement allows Kenyan herdsmen to graze their animals on
the other side of the border in case of a persistent drought on
the Kenyan side, the report added.
</P>
<P>
The incident forced the Kenyan herdsmen to return with more
than 2,000 assorted animals to the Kenyan side of the border.
</P>
<P>
The pastoral communities in the border areas of the two countries
have traditionally engaged in cattle rustling across the Kenyan
and Ugandan borders.
</P>
<P>
Late last year, Kenya and Uganda agreed to establish a
regional peace secretariat to ensure that any community which had
lost its animals was compensated and severe punishment was meted
on the raiders.
</P>
<P>
On February 15, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi promised that
his government would do everything to eradicate rustling and
ordered a major cattle branding exercise for easy identification
of stolen animals. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
