<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Towns Become Economic Giants in East China (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Rapid expansion of small towns has not only promoted rural
industrialization, but also helped solve the problem of surplus
labor. The aggregate population of these small towns has reached
more than 14 million, accounting for one third of the province's
total, according to statistics, and the number of farmers who work
for township enterprises there is more than 60 percent of the
province's total working in township enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Chai said that Zhejiang is making progress in its rural
urbanization, which is also in response to the national endeavor
to "strictly control the size of large cities, moderately develop
medium-sized and small cities, and actively develop small towns."
</P>
<P>
The province is performing reform tests on 46 selected towns,
with the aim of summing up experiences to design a management
system and operation mechanism that caters to the socialist market
economy, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The efforts involve everything from household registration to
land transfers, grain sales, and social security.
</P>
<P>
In doing so, the provincial government expects small towns to
grow into development centers for second and tertiary industries,
processing and marketing centers for agricultural and sideline
products, and bases to promote rural culture, education, science
and technology, as well as exchange or service centers for rural
labor, information, skilled workers, and finance.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang is expected to build one hundred small modern towns by
the turn of the century, while some bigger towns will be developed
into small and medium-sized cities, according to Chai. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
