<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Small Towns Become Economic Giants in East China  (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Longgang was a dilapidated
fishing village a dozen years ago but now presents an image of a
modern "mini-city", with 20-storey buildings, sidewalk, lawns,
neon lights advertising everything in the downtown area, and more.
</P>
<P>
Located in eastern Zhejiang Province, it is the first small
town in China to be built by farmers' money, and has become a
model of urbanization for China's rural areas.
</P>
<P>
Zhejiang now has 965 towns, a sharp rise from the 167 in 1978,
about the time China started its reforms and open-up policy.
</P>
<P>
Huang Zongke, the head of the town government, said that
Longgang has become a regional economic center, with last year's
industrial output value accounting for 40 percent of the county's
total. Wenzhou, whose jurisdiction Longgang falls under, has 30
economically-advantaged towns that contributed more than 60
percent of both the city's total industrial output and revenues in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
"Small towns are now an important revenue generator in the
rural economy of our province," Chai Songyue, vice governor of
Zhejiang, told Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
The towns are home to most of the area's rural businesses and
represent three fourths of Zhejiang's economy at present.
According to Chai, township enterprises are playing a leading role
in terms of enterprise development, quality, and science and
technology development in the province's rural economy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
