<HEADLINE> Middle East Business Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The following are business
briefs from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Electronica '97 will be held at the Tel Aviv
Fairgrounds from March 25-27, reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
Some 150 local electronics companies are expected to display
their goods. Foreign firms expected to attend the trade show
include Onel Electronics, a Turkish company that manufactures
parts for electronics companies.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Palestinians will have their first iron
factory, according to a report of The Jerusalem Times weekly.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian President Yasser Arafat laid the foundation stone
for the iron factory in Jericho recently.
</P>
<P>
Yacoub Hassouneh, owner of the factory, said the project is
very important for the Palestinian economy and for building the
foundation of a Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- The Britain-based Economist Advisory Group
Ltd. suggests that Israel's full exporting potential to the EU is
not being realized to the tune of hundreds of millions of
dollars, reported The Jerusalem Post today.
</P>
<P>
EU barriers has caused Israel large trade deficit with the
EU. According to the Central Bureau of Statistics, Israel's trade
deficit in 1996, excluding the diamond sector, totaled 9.3
billion U.S. dollars, and 72 percent or 6.7 billion dollar of the
overall figure was in trade with the EU.
</P>
<P>
NICOSIA -- Cypriot jewellers have laid their eyes on a new
export market -- the Middle East market, which is estimated to
bring them well over 10 million Cyprus pounds (about 20 million
U.S. dollars) in foreign exchange revenue.
</P>
<P>
A group of local jewellery manufacturers is expected to
attend the 1997 International Jewellery Dubai Exhibition which
will take place at the Dubai World Trade Center from March
26-30, 1997, according to local media reports.
</P>
<P>
Phytos Neophytou, a board member of the Cypriot Association of
Jewellers, said that the Middle East market has great potential
for Cypriot jewellers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
