<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kuchma Reaffirms Ukraine's Stand on NATO Expansion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Ukrainian President Leonid Kuchma
has reiterated that NATO expansion should proceed with the
participation of Ukraine and Russia, the Interfax News Agency
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Kuchma, who was on vacation in the western Ukrainian city of
Lviv, made the remarks at a press conference on Wednesday after a
meeting with visiting Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine does not allow that the eastern expansion of the
western military alliance places Ukraine in a "grey area" of
security in eastern Europe, the president said.
</P>
<P>
Unlike Moscow, Kiev does not oppose NATO's expansion plan,
which is expected to admit ex-Warsaw Pact countries, but it calls
for a nuclear-free zone in central and eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
NATO should sign an accord with Russia and Ukraine to avoid
creating such a "grey area," Kuchma said.
</P>
<P>
Italy and Ukraine hold similar views on the issues of bilateral
relationship and European security, Kuchma told the press.
</P>
<P>
Prodi, who came here four months after Italian President Oscar
Scalfaro's Ukraine tour, said both sides advocate closer
cooperation in the European institution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
