<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Overseas Funds for China's Building Materials Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China has introduced five
billion US dollars in overseas funds into its building materials
industry and is trying to attract even more to widen the scale.
</P>
<P>
The funds will be used to produce new building materials,
inorganic nonmetallic materials, and equipment to manufacture
building materials, according to a senior official with the State
Administration of Building Materials, which is asking overseas
enterprises involved to strictly abide by Chinese laws and rules
and to answer industry needs and to provide advice.
</P>
<P>
The official noted that the use of overseas funds should take
the industry's product mix restructuring into consideration as
well as environmental protection. All overseas-funded projects
must meet international standards for environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
Overseas funds will be introduced mainly for production of
cement, glass and ceramics. The country is encouraging
construction of large cement projects and technology upgrading in
small cement plants. In ceramic production, focus will be placed
on improving product quality.
</P>
<P>
The State Administration of Building Materials will also put
limits on overseas-funded enterprises, and will not allow
exclusively foreign-owned cement and glass enterprises. Co-funded
technological transformations or share-holding by foreigners in
key state-owned enterprises, whose products are listed in the
country's production plans, will be allowed only with approval
from government departments.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, overseas-funded projects should pay attention to
technical upgrading. China particularly encourages establishment
of research and development centers for glass fibre reinforced
plastic, and other new building materials, for sustained
development of related technology.
</P>
<P>
The administration says that production equipment in
overseas-funded cement, glass, and ceramics enterprises should be
purchased through domestic and international bidding and at least
50 percent of the the equipment should be domestic.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
