<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Scientists Suggest Proper Legislation for Clone Technology </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Chinese scientists have
suggested that legislation is necessary for control of potential
dangers that may arise from the clone technology.
</P>
<P>
Attending the annual sessions of China's parliament and its top
government advisory body here, the scientists agree that the birth of the
first clone sheep announced earlier this week is a major
scientific breakthrough.
</P>
<P>
Last Monday, scientists in Scotland announced that they had
produced the world's first clone animal from the combination of a
cellnucleus fro an adult sheep's mammary gland and an
unfertilized egg from the same sheep.
</P>
<P>
Comparing it with that of nuclear energy, genetiist Zhang
Jiaming said that clone technology can be used to both
benefit and harm the human race.
</P>
<P>
Zhang, a deputy to the National People's Congress (NPC), heads
a research institute of biological products under the Ministry
of Public Health.
</P>
<P>
Zhang and his colleagues suggested that laws be enacted to
control the use of clone technology within a limited scope. They
agree that the technology should be off-limit for the
duplication of human beings.
</P>
<P>
However, the scientists said there is no need for panic since
the technology has only made initial progress.
</P>
<P>
According to clone theories, a human being's cells do not die
with him or her. The clone technology may enable scientists to
duplicate the DNAs contained in any cell and develop it into an
identical person with the deceased one.
</P>
<P>
The cloning of the sheep was regarded by some as the prelude to
the technical duplication of human beings, and unsurprisingly, it
worries some scientists, ethicists, and government officials for
its complex ethical implications.
</P>
<P>
Chen Shouyi, head of the Institute of Genetics under the
Chinese Academy of Sciences (CAS), said the sheep cloning
technology will help with efforts to maintain purebred sheep,
and it should not be stopped simply because of some potential
dangers it may present.
</P>
<P>
Chen, a member of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference National Committee, used to be a member of a research
team which cloned a cow from embryonic cells last April. However,
the Scottish team was the first to make a clone from adult animal
cell. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
