<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria to Raise Prices of Electricity, Communications </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The prices of electricity and
phone calls in Bulgaria will soar again next month.
</P>
<P>
Electricity will be sold at 36 leva (about two US cents) per
kilowatt-hour as of March 1 and the price will shortly rise again
to 3.5 US cents per kwh, the government said. Phone call charges
will rise from 0.18 cents to 1.2 cents for a local call and prices
for long distance and international calls will also go up.
</P>
<P>
Energy prices rose by 400 percent last year after three lots of
price hikes imposed by the government. The latest round of
increases were due to come into force on February 1 but were
delayed.
</P>
<P>
The government said electricity subisidies worth 20 million
Ecus (23 million U.S. dollars) offered by the European Union will
be available to the 150,000 poorest families.
</P>
<P>
Bulgaria is facing a serious crisis caused by several years of
mismanagement.
</P>
<P>
The Socialist government resigned earlier this month under
pressure from the opposition for failing to deal with the
country's growing economic problems. A caretaker government was
formed on February 12 to manage the country until general
elections are held in April. 
</P>
</TEXT>
