<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Spokesman on Election of HK Deputies to Ninth NPC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong will elect 36
deputies to the Ninth National People's Congress, China's
legislature, a NPC spokesman said in Beijing today.
</P>
<P>
At the first press conference of the Fifth Session of the
Eighth NPC, which is due tomorrow, Zhou Jue, spokesman for the
session, said that the method for the election of Hong Kong
deputies to the next NPC will be discussed and decided during the
session.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with a draft method deliberated by the 23rd
Session of the Eighth NPC Standing Committee at the end of last
year, he said, a meeting of election will be established, which
will be composed of members of the Selection Committee for
choosing the first government of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (HKSAR) who are citizens of Chinese
nationality.
</P>
<P>
The number of the deputies is decided according to the Election
Law of the NPC, which stipulates that one NPC deputy will be
chosen from every 220,000 urban residents.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that even if it is passed by the current NPC
session, the method is still a transitional one that will be
applied to the Ninth NPC only.
</P>
<P>
The term of the current NPC will expire in March of 1998, while
deputies to the Ninth NPC should be elected before the end of
January, 1998.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question from a Hong Kong reporter on whether
the principles of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong" will be fully implemented after the passing
of Deng Xiaoping, Zhou said it is the Chinese government's
consistent stance to carry out these principles unswervingly, and
there is no possibility of any change.
</P>
<P>
He said it was the long-cherished aspiration of Deng Xiaoping
to achieve the return of Hong Kong to the motherland with the
principles of "one country, two systems" and "Hong Kong people
governing Hong Kong."
</P>
<P>
"The great concept of 'one country, two systems' set forth by
Deng Xiaoping has found repeated expressions in laws adopted by
the NPC and various documents released by the central government,
and it is now deeply rooted in the minds of the people," he added.
</P>
<P>
A "New York Times" correspondent asked if the current NPC
session will deliberate on China's signing of two United Nations
covenants on economic, social and cultural rights and on civil and
political rights.
</P>
<P>
"It is not on the agenda of the current session. However, the
relevant departments of the Chinese government are giving
considerations to this matter," Zhou said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
