<HEADLINE> Thai Government Urged to Revive Exports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 28 (Xinhua) -- A Thai private sector joint
committee has urged all government bodies to work together in a
bid to manage the economy effectively.
</P>
<P>
In a communique, available here today, the committee said
urgent actions must be taken to restore Thailand's competitive
edge.
</P>
<P>
The private sector committee, comprising representatives of the
Chamber of Commerce, the Federation of Thai Industries and the
Thai Bankers' Association, noted that the drive to improve export
performance must continue and recommended that the government cut
operating cost, reduce bureaucratic red tape and offer value-added
tax refunds more quickly.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the private sector is willing to make
sacrifice in the short term for longer term gains.
</P>
<P>
The committee said it would work with state enterprises and
related trade associations to promote the tourism, hotel, textiles
and garments, gems and jewelry, electrical appliances, and
handicraft sectors.
</P>
<P>
Although key economic indicators released this week for January
have shown slight improvement in some economic sectors, Bank of
Thailand officials cautioned that a clearer sign is needed before
proclaiming that the worst is over.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the Finance Ministry announced that January's
exports were up 1.2 percent from the previous month, compared with
the 0.2 percent negative growth for the whole 1996.
</P>
<P>
The balance of payments in January recorded a surplus of 24.7
billion baht (988 million US dollars), a sharp reversal from the
19.2 billion baht (768 million dollar) deficit in December.
</P>
</TEXT>
