<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NPC Session Spokesman on Amendments to Criminal Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- An revision to China's
17-year-old Criminal Law in the upcoming Fifth Session of the
Eighth National People's Congress will be a major event in the
development of the country's legal and judicial system, a
spokesman for the NPC Session said today.
</P>
<P>
It would substantially help the country to achieve its goals of
effecting the practice of rule of law in China and improving its
legal framework, said Zhou Jue, spokesman for the NPC's Fifth
Session.
</P>
<P>
"However," he noted, "the principles and tasks of cracking down
on crimes, protecting the interests of people and safeguarding the
cause of socialism as provided in the existing law are correct and
will not be altered."
</P>
<P>
He explained that the sweeping amendments to be made to the law
are aimed to cope with the changes of the situation and the times.
For instance, computer crimes, money laundering and crimes related
to the value-added tax invoices emerging in recent years have to
be dealt with in the law, as well as the crimes of smuggling and
corruption, which are more severe today and must be given harsher
penalties or curbed through other ways.
</P>
<P>
As the most noteable changes in the draft criminal code, three
major principles of criminal justice will be further clarified.
Namely, crimes and penalties must be decided by the law, penalties
should comply with crimes, all people are equal before the law,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
The analogy measures included in the existing law have been
annulled in the draft code to the NPC Session.
</P>
<P>
The new draft has set still more explicit terms on crimes and
penalties, which would effectively reduce wilful practices by law
enforcement personnel and protect the legitimate rights and
interests of individuals, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Another amendment was introduced to revise the definition of
the counter-revolutionary crimes and redefine them as offenses to
jeopardize state security, he added.
</P>
<P>
Stipulations on debatement from penalty, release on parole,
surrender and meritorious service by the convicted were also
improved and made more specific, the spokesman said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
