<HEADLINE> US Treasury Urges Debt Payment to Finance Institutions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- United States Treasury
Secretary Robert Rubin today urged the Congress to pay the huge
debt the U.S. owes to the World Bank and regional development
banks.
</P>
<P>
Rubin asked a House panel to consider President Bill Clinton's
budget request for 1.6 billion U.S. dollars for international
financial institutions such as the World Bank, the International
Monetary Fund and the regional development banks.
</P>
<P>
Failure to pay the debts would jeopardize the U.S. leadership
of these financial institutions, he said.
</P>
<P>
"We make this budget request because it is in our economic and
national security interests and because we have to play our fair
part in budget sharing," he added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. was the world's largest and richest economic power, he
said: "Yet we are the largest debtor to the United Nations, the
only major country in arrears to the World Bank, and account for
the lion's share of arrears to the regional development banks."
</P>
<P>
In its budget plan for fiscal year 1998, the Clinton
administration had proposed spending on the international
financial institutions.
</P>
<P>
To date, the U.S. owes 1.5 billion dollars to the World Bank
and the regional development banks.
</P>
<P>
The total debt the U.S. owes to the financial institutions
exceeds the debt it owes to the United Nations which is more than
one billion dollars.  
</P>
</TEXT>
