<HEADLINE> Canada's Travel Expenditure Deficit Rises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Canada's travel account deficit
reached 2.4 billion U.S. dollars in 1996, up six percent against
1995, Statistics Canada reported today.
</P>
<P>
This was the first time in four years that Canada saw its
deficit on travel spending rise.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, spending by Canadians travelling abroad jumped 8.6
percent from the previous year, to an unprecedented 11.3 billion
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, foreign travelers spent 8.9 billion dollars in
Canada, up 9.3 percent from 1995.
</P>
<P>
Canada saw a record surplus in money spent by visitors from
countries other than the United States.
</P>
<P>
These travelers spent more than 4.1 billion dollars in Canada
while Canadians spent 3.9 billion dollars in return.
</P>
<P>
The overall travel deficit resulted from higher spending in the
U.S. by Canadians, the agency said.
</P>
<P>
Last year, American visitors spent a total of 4.8 billion
dollars in Canada, up 7.8 percent over 1995, while Canadians spent
7.4 billion dollars in the U.S., up 9.6 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
