<HEADLINE> Czech Assembly Approves Border Accord </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PRAGUE, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The assembly of the Czech
Republic Wednesday approved, after a heated discussion, a border
accord with its former federation partner, the Slovak Republic.
</P>
<P>
The law was passed with 141 votes in favor, 37 objections and
14 abstentions.
</P>
<P>
Czech Interior Minister Jan Ruml said later: "Czech and
Slovakia will be close neighbors forever, but the border for the
two sovereign states must be settled in a form of law."
</P>
<P>
The accord, agreed in January 1996 by both countries' interior
ministers and already approved by the Slovak parliament, would
have shortened the border by 33 km, to 252 km, straightening out
curves drawn after the split of Czechoslovakia in 1993.
</P>
<P>
The border trouble arose from a plan to exchange two villages,
the now Czech village of U Sabotu, and Slovak village of
Sidonie. This would have meant a shift of 452 hectares of land to
one or the other side at different places, allowing the border to
follow a more logical line. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
