<HEADLINE> Nepali PM to Reduce Cabinet Size After Confidence Vote </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Nepali Prime Minister Sher
Bahadur Deuba has finally agreed to trim his 47-member coalition
cabinet after his main ruling party directed him to do so early
this month.
</P>
<P>
In a statement issued here Thursday, Deuba vowed to reduce the
cabinet size only after his three-party government obtains a vote
of confidence in the upcoming winter session of parliament
starting from next Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
He requested lawmakers of his Nepali Congress (NC) party and
other coalition partners to present themselves unitedly in the
parliament session and vote for the government.
</P>
<P>
Deuba is expected to seek a vote of confidence for his
government during the session under opposition pressure since it
was reduced into minority status by an opposition challenge last
December.
</P>
<P>
Thursday's statement was Deuba's first public response to his
party's call for a reduction of cabinet size made at a party
central committee meeting early this month.
</P>
<P>
The NC party leadership directed Deuba to trim his cabinet to
"polish the image of the government and to enhance its
effectiveness."
</P>
<P>
So far over two dozens of MPs of the NC party have threatened
to be absent from the parliament session if the prime minister
does not make the reshuffle before the session, local reports said
today.
</P>
<P>
They insisted that the cabinet should be reduced before the
government secures the vote of confidence in the lower house of
parliament.  
</P>
</TEXT>
