<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Reiterates Joining EMU on Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minister Romano
Prodi reiterated today that Italy is on track to be part of
European Monetary Union from the start.
</P>
<P>
"Italy intends to present itself at the appointed time for
monetary union with all its papers in order so that we can be lead
players in all the next steps Europe will make," Prodi said during
a question and answer session in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Prodi said that heads of state and government of the 15
European Union nations would assess their own achievements in
January 1999, and then "decisions will be made jointly instead of
being made by those who consider themselves as having the
authority of a teacher marking his students."
</P>
<P>
This was believed to be a veiled reference to Germany, where
many economists and leaders have made it clear they don't want
Italy to be in the first wave of countries joining the single
currency because they think the weak lira would drag down the
currency.
</P>
<P>
The prime minister said a Europe without Italy would not be
able to represent the full complex dimension of the continent and
would lose the ability to be coherent on the Mediterranean scene.
</P>
<P>
He also told the Senate that he had spoken earlier today to
French President Jacques Chirac on the phone, and both sides
reached "full consensus" on the common strategy of the Maastricht
Treaty for Mediterranean countries.
</P>
<P>
The ANSA news agency took the "full consensus" as referring to
issues in Europe, including the single currency and the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization's eastward expansion, and a signal of
"reconciliation" after Italy criticized France for conducting
nuclear tests and France accused Italy of devaluing the lira to
boost its competitiveness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
