<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Seeks Leniency for Colombia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTAFE DE BOGOTA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- United States
Ambassador to Colombia Myles Frechette has asked the U.S. to give
a conditional certification on Colombia's drug combating efforts
if the Colombian Congress approves extradition legislation within
the next six months.
</P>
<P>
The "El Expectador" newspaper said today that Frechette's
request was sent last week to the U.S. Department of State. It
asked for the granting of conditional certification for national
security reasons, if the new law which also provides for stiffer
sentences for drug traffickers is approved.
</P>
<P>
The certification is an annual assessment in which Washington
examines the performance of 32 countries in combating drug
trafficking. The U.S. then decides to certify a list of countries
as cooperating fully with U.S. efforts to fight drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
United Statea Undersecretary of State Robert Gelbard had
received reports from U.S. departments, including the Central
Intelligence Agency (CIA), the Drug Enforcement Administration
(DEA) and the Federal Bureau of Investigations (FBI), demanding
that Colombia be disqualified for the second time, due to
Colombian President Ernesto Samper's lack of collaboration in
fighting trafficking.
</P>
<P>
Ambassador Frechette's report was the only one favoring
certification for Colombia.
</P>
<P>
Last year,the United States disqualified Afganistan, Burma,
Colombia, Iran, Nigeria and Syria. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
