<HEADLINE> Southwest Province to Become China's Leading Chemical Base </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China's Sichuan Province is
set to allocate 11.2 billion yuan over the next four years for
building a chemical industry base in the southern part of the
province.
</P>
<P>
The industrial base will cover five counties and comprise 30
projects in fertilizers, farm chemicals, refined chemical
products, caustic soda, tires, and equipment.
</P>
<P>
Southern Sichuan has 97 chemical works which had four billion
yuan in output value in 1996, accounting for 31.5 percent of the
total output value of the province's chemical industry.
</P>
<P>
The province plans to turn the Luzhou Natural Gas Corporation
into one of the 18 key chemical bases designated by the central
government in coming years.
</P>
<P>
Other projects to be started soon include a synthetic ammonia
production line with an annual capacity of 300,000 tons, a urea
production line for 520,000 tons annually, and concentrated rare
earth fertilizer production. 
</P>
</TEXT>
