<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Internet Narrows Gaps, Speeds Competition: Intel President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The Internet will narrow gaps
between developing and developed nations and accelerate
competitiveness globally, Intel Corporation Chief Executive
Officer and President, Dr. Andrew Grove, told Xinhua in a recent
interview.
</P>
<P>
"The Internet has the power to level the playing field between
societies." Grove said, "Access to information allows the time
between decisions to decrease, which accelerates competitiveness
globally."
</P>
<P>
Giving his vision of the emerging "network society", the
central theme of the 1997 annual meeting of the Geneva-based World
Economic Forum, Grove said the network society was overwhelmingly
positive.
</P>
<P>
"For business and government it is a case of economic
competition and development," he said.
</P>
<P>
Data transference was still slow in the present Internet due to
slow or busy communications links. In the wake of that, Intel was
designing a Personal computer able to compensate for some of these
problems.
</P>
<P>
Intel, the world's largest semiconductor producer, introduced
its latest Pentium processors with multi-media chip technology in
early January. The new processors are said to be far better at
compressing and decompressing data, squeezing it down so that it
can fit into a smaller bandwidth connection.
</P>
<P>
Referring to China's computer technology, Grove said: "China is
leapfrogging ahead of many western countries." He was extremely
impressed with the speed with which China was moving into the
"Information Age".
</P>
<P>
Speaking about Intel's cooperation with China, the president
mentioned Intel's Computer Architecture Laboratory in Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
Intel was helping numerous Chinese software and hardware
developers to develop technology to make Internet access more
rewarding and enjoyable to Chinese speakers around the world, he
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
