<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesian House Approves Budget But Calls for </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's House of
Representatives approved the 1997-98 draft state budget without
any changes Thursday, but urged the government to boost tax
revenue and reduce current account deficit.
</P>
<P>
The house's four factions, which approved the budget at a
plenary session, also criticizing the government for increasing
civil servants', soldiers' and pensioners' salaries.
</P>
<P>
President Soeharto presented the country's 1997-98 budget draft
in January, with a total revenue expected to reach 101.1 trillion
rupiah (43.2 billion US dollars), or nominally up 11.6 percent on
the current budget.
</P>
<P>
Domestic revenues, which rely heavily on taxes, are expected to
exceed 64 trillion rupiah (27.35 billion dollars), an increase of
almost 16 percent from the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The four factions urged the government to further increase tax
revenue, especially from direct taxes (income and property taxes),
because the ratio of tax receipts against gross domestic product
(GDP) was the lowest in ASEAN (association of southeast Asian
nations) countries.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN groups Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the Philippines,
Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
The factions also called for special attention to the worsening
balance of payments problem. The current account deficit is
projected to reach 9.8 billion US dollars in 1997-98 or almost 4
percent of the GDP.
</P>
<P>
The country's fiscal year starts on April 1 and ends on March
31 next year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
