<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Producers Demand Protection Against U.S. Dumping </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRASILIA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Brazil's industrial body, the
CNI, is calling on President Fernando Henrique Cardoso to impose
sanctions against a U.S. conglomerate it accuses of dumping its
products on the Brazilian market.
</P>
<P>
The National Industries Confederation has accused American
Natural Soda Ash of selling the raw material barrilla on the
Brazilian market at artificially low prices, threatening Brazil's
domestic producers.
</P>
<P>
Barrilla is a raw material used in the manufacture of more than
100 products, mainly glass, textiles, and detergent.
</P>
<P>
ANSAC is a U.S. cartel of barrilla exporters formed by
U.S. firms manufacturing the product, which is forbidden by the
U.S. Congress from operating domestically, a report by the CNI
said.
</P>
<P>
Its dumping activities have caused 23 companies worldwide to
close down.
</P>
<P>
The European Union has already banned ANSAC from operating in
Europe to protect its domestic producers, CNI president Fernando
Bezerra said.
</P>
<P>
The report called on the Brazilian government to raise tariffs
on barilla imports, provide compensation to domestic producers
and anti-dumping penalties on the company. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
