<HEADLINE> Thailand to Close Ties with Indian Ocean Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Thailand has applied to join
the Indian ocean rim consultative business network in a bid to
find new markets and sources of raw materials for domestic
production.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken after Thailand noted the great potential of
the market in the region which has rich resources and about
one-third of the world's population, Savaraj Sachchamarga, deputy
secretary-general of the Thai Chamber of Commerce was quoted today
by local press as saying.
</P>
<P>
The forum combines businessmen and experts of 23 member
countries including Australia, Bahrain, India, Indonesia, Iran,
Kenya, Kuwait, Myanmar, Oman, Pakistan, Saudi Arabia, Singapore,
South Africa, Sri Lanka and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
It is scheduled to meet in March to discuss trade, investment,
marine affairs and transport, customs, environmental and energy
issues, and information technology.
</P>
<P>
"Thailand does not want to miss this train and it will join the
meeting as an observer," Savaraj said.
</P>
<P>
Indian ocean rim countries accounted for 18.11 percent of
Thailand's total trade value in 1995, and 18.35 percent between
January and November last year.  
</P>
