<HEADLINE> Russia Opposes NATO-Sponsored Maneuver </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia has refused to join a
NATO-sponsored military exercise in the Black Sea in August,
warning that the maneuver will further complicate the situation in
the region.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Andreyev told reporters
here today that Russia is clearly aware of the unspoken purpose
behind the exercise, but he did not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
The exercise to be held in waters close to Yevpatoriya, a port
on Ukraine's Crimean peninsular, will be carried out by NATO
members -- the United States, Britain, Germany and Turkey -- along
with Ukraine, Bulgaria and Romania.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the exercise, which is being held under NATO's
Partnership for Peace program, is to assess the ability of fleets
from different countries to coordinate during joint military
action.
</P>
<P>
Russia has long been opposed to NATO's eastward expansion plan,
describing it a potential threat to its security.
</P>
<P>
Russia and Ukraine are still embroiled in a long-standing
dispute over the division of the Black Sea Fleet of the former
Soviet Union and Russia's use of the naval base of Sevastopol, a
port on the Crimean peninsula. 
</P>
</TEXT>
