<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WHO Director-General: Severe Lack of Medicines in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The dire situation of Iraq's
health care system has prompted World Health Organization (WHO)
Director-General Hiroshi Nakajima to call on everyone involved in
the U.N.-Iraq "oil for food" deal to make sure the operation is a
success.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima, fresh from a four-day visit to Iraq, was shocked by
the near breakdown of Iraq's health care system, which he
described as "reeling under the pressure of being deprived of
medicine, other basic supplies and spare parts."
</P>
<P>
Nakajima went to the Gulf country on a fact-finding mission and
to observe the implementation of the United Nations Security
Council Resolution 986 authorizing the six-month sale of Iraqi oil
in return for the provision of food and medicines.
</P>
<P>
Iraq, a major oil-producing country, has been banned from
selling oil on the international market following its invasion of
Kuwait in August, 1990.
</P>
<P>
Nakajima said Iraq's "inability to cope with and provide
services which the Iraqi people used to receive is of grave
concern".
</P>
<P>
He noted that stocks of drugs and medical supplies in Iraqi
government drug warehouses and pharmacies were extremely
low. Basic medical materials, such as disposable syringes,
bandages and dressings are not available. Diseases that were
virtually under control are re-emerging.
</P>
<P>
During his visit, Nakajima was told about the concerns of the
Iraqi government over delays in receiving medicine and medical
supplies, the WHO said.
</P>
<P>
In view of that, Nakajima urged all parties concerned to
"develop a spirit of closer cooperation in making this operation a
success, keeping in mind the urgent need to improve the health
conditions of the people of Iraq." 
</P>
</TEXT>
