<HEADLINE> China Eyes More Overseas Funds for Power Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China hopes to use 25 billion
US dollars-worth of overseas funds in its power sector in the
Ninth Five-Year-Plan period (1996-2000).
</P>
<P>
This means a doubling of the proportion of foreign investment
as compared with the country's total investment for the power
industry -- from 10 percent to 20 percent by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
Shi Dazhen, minister of the power industry, who was here
recently for a national conference on the power industry, said
that pooling funds through various channels, including the
introduction of overseas funds, will remain a major task
challenging China's power industry.
</P>
<P>
According to him, China made actual use of 12.2 billion US
dollars in overseas funds for the construction of 75 large and
medium-sized power projects from 1979 to 1995, with a combined
generating capacity of 49.09 million kw, accounting for 10 percent
of the country's total investment in the power sector during the
same period.
</P>
<P>
China has worked out a series of detailed policies to encourage
overseas investors to invest in its power sector, which have
proved effective.
</P>
<P>
The participants in the meeting agreed to continue to try to
increase international cooperation, with the purpose of obtaining
more overseas funds.  
</P>
</TEXT>
