<HEADLINE> Shenyang To Clean Up Polluted Canal Water </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Foul water in a canal
surrounding Shenyang, the capital of Liaoning Province, is
expected to be cleaned up after 10 deputies to the fifth session
of the Eighth People's Congress asked about it on Tuesday, today's
"China Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing-based newspaper also says that a survey in 1995
indicated the canal with two others around the city were heavily
polluted or even dried up from March to November every year
sending out awful smells. This is caused by cutting off the water
source from Dahoufang reservoir, an hour's drive away in the
northeastern suburb.
</P>
<P>
This reservoir was built in the 1950s. It has a capacity of
1.56 billion cubic metres, of which 14 million cubic metres of
water go into the canal for the city's environmental protection.
</P>
<P>
With the economic boom, the amount of water filling the lakes
through the canal has decreased considerably.
</P>
<P>
Ten deputies to the provincial People's Congress suggested
asking the local government to solve the problem. They got a
prompt response from the government. Xu Wencai, vice-governor in
charge of water's resources said that, a decision was made that
another 6 million cubic metres of water will be added to the city
for environmental purpose every year.
</P>
<P>
Xu also said more than 3.6 million US dollars was spent on a
dam to raise the level of the river so that water can be filled
into the Northern Canal.
</P>
<P>
Liaoning Province, an industrial hub with a poor water supply,
has resolved to spend an equivalent of 1.3 billion US dollars to
clear up Liaohe River, the province's main water source, by
setting up 21 water treatment plants in the next 15 years, the
paper says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
