<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev and visiting Turkmen President Saparmurad Niyazov
signed a declaration here on Thursday to strengthen their
bilateral relations.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed that relations between the two have
reached a new stage, and the document made a good basis for
further bilateral cooperation in technology, economy and trade.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the Caspian Sea, the two sides said it was a main
task for the countries around the sea to draw up and sign an
international law on the sea. All the Caspian countries had the
right to develop the resources in the sea.
</P>
<P>
Talking about the future of the Commonwealth of Independent
States (CIS), Nazarbayev said the CIS members should strengthen
their internal cooperation.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov said relations between Turkmenistan and the CIS
depended on whether it was good for the country's sovereignty,
security and economic development.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also signed 17 other agreements mainly on the
status of the Caspian Sea and on cooperation in technology,
education and trade.
</P>
<P>
Niyazov, who is here for a two-day official visit, will attend a
meeting to be held Friday in Alma Ata by the five central Asian
countries on the ecological issues of the Aral Sea. 
