<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Animals in Shanghai Zoo Enjoy Winter Time </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- All the animals in the
Shanghai Wildlife Zoo, the first of its kind in the country, have
been doing well since the beginning of this winter.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to good care by the zoo's staff, more than 5,000 wild
animals of 130 species have survived the winter, said Xia
Shuzhong, an employee with the breeding department.
</P>
<P>
About 30,000 sq m of grass and more than 50,000 trees and
flowers have been planted in the 300-million-yuan zoo since it
opened in Nanhui County, outside Shanghai in 1995, providing
better living conditions for the wildlife there.
</P>
<P>
Having enough food, the zoo's 16 Chinese alligators, a
hibernating animal, fell into a deep sleep in late autumn. They
were so absorbed in sleep that they did not wake up when the
workers moved them into insulated sheds. The spring will be here
soon, but they are still sound asleep.
</P>
<P>
Also with the habit of hibernating, black bears were more
active than the alligators during this mild winter. Not caged,
they can wander over large areas of the zoo.
</P>
<P>
The zoo has seen its population boom this winter, with more
than 50 animals of 16 species born, including four Northeast
tigers and 14 African lions.
</P>
<P>
Water birds, which were the "original residents" of the zoo,
brought their relatives and friends to nest on the zoo's lake
during the migrating season.
</P>
<P>
Two lion cubs, born on the first day of the Chinese lunar new
year, are the most popular "stars" in the zoo these days. The poor
cubs were abandoned by their mother as soon as they were born and
in badly need of milk. So the zoo workers had to advertise for a
"wet nurse" in a newspaper, and finally selected from among 50
candidates a dog named A Huang as the "honorary mother lion".
</P>
<P>
A Huang had produced seven puppies just the day after the lion
cubs were born and had no trouble feeding the cubs, as well as her
puppies, milk. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Adopt New Regulations on Consumer Rights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- China will adopt a new set of
regulations to deal with cases of infringement on consumer rights,
China Daily said today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile consumer protection will be given a high profile in
March when a special month-long publicity campaign is held to
inform the public of their legal rights.
</P>
<P>
The country plans the establishment of a nationwide social
supervision network to help protect consumers' legal rights and
create a fair consumer environment in China, the State
Administration for Industry and Commerce said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The administration is mobilizing over 30,000 local offices for
industry and commerce to improve investigations and the handling
of consumer infringement cases, said Gan Guoping, deputy director
of the administration.
</P>
<P>
"As part of the State administration's measures to protect
consumers, this effort will help broaden the official channels to
hear and accept consumer complaints in China," the paper quoted
Gan as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said the State administration has designed March as a
special month to publicize the three-year-old law on consumer
protection. The promotion campaign will highlight legal rights set
by China's consumer laws, other relevant state and local
regulations, and the functions and roles and measures of the
administration in protecting consumers.
</P>
<P>
Gan said local administrations for industry and commerce will
co-ordinate with local People's Congress on the drafting of
relevant local rules.
</P>
<P>
"We aim to enhance public awareness about their own rights,
improve public understanding of the roles of administration
offices for industry and commerce and build a sound basis for the
establishment of the social supervision network for the protection
of consumers in China this year," said the official.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the administrations will strengthen supervision
and inspection of the implementation of the laws and regulations
on consumer protection.
</P>
<P>
They will also continue to conduct close-cooperation with
commodity inspection departments in the supervision and checking
of the quality of major imported commodities such as motorcycles,
TV sets, air-conditioners and cosmetics as a step to ban fake and
inferior imports and smuggling.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Chinese administrations for industry and commerce
investigated and dealt with almost 15,000 cases of consumers'
rights infringements.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
