<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zhejiang Province Successful in Protecting Land </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANGZHOU, February 28 (Xinhua) -- East China's Zhejiang
Province has made substantial achievements in protecting its
valuable cultivated land which had been decreasing for a long time
in the recent past due to industrial and urban expansions.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the province newly cultivated 7,900 ha, compared with
7,700 ha which were occupied for non-farming purposes in the same
year. This enabled the province to achieve balanced land-use for
the first time, according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
At present, the province has an average of a mere 0.036 ha of
cultivated land per person, which is less than half of the
country's average.
</P>
<P>
During the Eighth Five-Year Plan period (1991-1995), the
acreage of the province's farmland shrank by 21,300 ha every year.
</P>
<P>
As of 1995, the situation has been eased, thanks to the efforts
made by local governments, as the drop in the acreage of local
farmland was 31 percentage points less than the figure for the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
Last year the province furthered the efforts to curb the
shrinking of farmland by 77.4 percent against the figure in 1995.
</P>
<P>
To this end, the provincial government issued three local laws
and regulations, while a responsibility system was established at
different levels of local government for protecting farmland.
</P>
<P>
Some local government officials have been punished for causing
farmland loss.
</P>
<P>
In the Ninth Five-Year Plan period (1996-2000), the provincial
government has ordered localities to open another 33,000 ha of new
cultivated land and upgrade 333,000 ha of low-yield farmland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
