<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Moderate Growth for Workers' Wages in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The excessive growth of wages
in China slowed and the unemployment rate remained low in 1996.
</P>
<P>
China had 148.6 million salaried workers by the end of last
year, roughly same as in the previous year, according to a
national conference on labor and wages held in this, China's
largest industrial center recently.
</P>
<P>
The total amount of wages of workers across the country last
year was 912 billion yuan, 12.6 percent up from 1995. The earnings
of each worker averaged 6,210 yuan in 1996, 12.9 percent higher
than the figure in the previous year.
</P>
<P>
After deducting price rises, the wages increased by 3.8 percent
last year, the lowest rise since 1992.
</P>
<P>
Over 30 provinces and cities have implemented the minimum
cost-of-living system to guarantee the basic needs of the people
with financial difficulties in urban districts.
</P>
<P>
A breakthrough was made in many provinces in the reform of the
wages system last year, according to the conference.
</P>
<P>
The emphasis of the wage reform this year will be on three
aspects:
</P>
<P>
-- The relationship of distribution among different trades will
be readjusted in a bid to narrow the income gap;
</P>
<P>
-- The country will rectify the order of distribution and make
everyone have a clearer understanding of distribution principles;
and
</P>
<P>
-- Areas chosen for experimenting with wage reforms will be
expanded from Beijing, Shenzhen and Chengdu cities to 10 provinces
and cities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
