<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russia to Update Its Armed Forces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Russia aims to lay a sound
foundation for its military with the modernization of weaponry by
2005 and the development of superior intelligence gathering and
information systems.
</P>
<P>
Andrei Kokoshin, Russia's first deputy defense minister, told a
press conference that this was part of the military reform to
update Russian armed forces.
</P>
<P>
Up to 50 or 60 percent of Russia's weaponry and military
technology in service is expected to be updated under the
modernization program.
</P>
<P>
The program will focus on reconnaissance, information
collection, logistics and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
A senior Russian defense official said that Russian army would
purchase about 350 tanks and 400 armored vehicles each year until
2005.
</P>
<P>
Tank and aircraft purchases would be kept at the lowest level
possible for the normal operation of Russia's military industry,
he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
