<HEADLINE> Firms Target House Building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The expected housing
construction boom in South China is luring major international
construction-related firms to cash in, today's China Daily reports.
</P>
<P>
They are targeting Building South China '97 and Construction
Technology China '97 exhibition shows which will be held March
11-14 at the China Foreign Trade Center in Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
Covering a floor space of 8,000 square metres, the fairs will
attract more than 200 exhibitors from 22 countries and regions,
including European Union countries, the United States, Canada,
Australia and Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Viet Nam Construction Department will visit the exhibitions to
establish and enhance trade and technology relations with China.
</P>
<P>
By the end of the century, China plans to build 1.2 billion
square metres -- 240 million square metres per year -- of housing,
said Hou Jie, China's construction minister.
</P>
<P>
In Guangdong Province alone, more than 200 million square
metres of housing will be built during the period. The interior
decorating industry has been developing rapidly. In 1996, business
volume amounted to more than 50 billion yuan (6.02 billion US
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The fairs are organized by Adsale Exhibition Services Ltd,
Guangdong Provincial Building Materials Co and China Foreign Trade
Center Group. They will showcase sanitary products, wall-paper and
covering, carpets, concrete equipment, construction engineering
machines, infrastructure equipment and building materials
machinery.
</P>
<P>
Also on exhibit will be building-related equipment like car
park security systems which are to meet the demand of modern
office building, hotels and shopping malls in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
