<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First Resettled Three Gorges Village Takes Shape </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YICHANG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Among thousands of villages
which have to be moved from the area of the Three Gorges
Hydropower Project now under construction, Zhujiawan Village is
the first to have completed the process.
</P>
<P>
The village, under the administration of Yichang County, Hubei
Province, has been completely renovated, with rows of newly-built
four-story apartments alongside cement roads.
</P>
<P>
Wei Xiangjie, the village's Communist Party secretary, told
Xinhua that Zhujiawan now has 286 households, with a total
population of 749.
</P>
<P>
According to Wei, the village began to move its population to
the new site in the second half of 1992, and by June 1993 all the
villagers had been resettled.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 the village generated a total industrial and
agricultural production value of 65.4 million yuan, compared with
20.71 million in 1993, while the villagers' per capita average
yearly income reached 5,880 yuan.
</P>
<P>
Wei attributed the achievements to the opportunities brought
about by the dam project-related resettlement, financial and
political assistance offered by the central government and other
parts of the country, and the wisdom of the villagers in grasping
the opportunities and working hard to enrich themselves.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Bin and his wife Tan Yulian said that their total income
was 21,000 yuan last year. Now the couple and their son are
leading a well-off life.
</P>
<P>
Yang Zhongfa, another Zhujiawan villager, works alone to
support his family, the poorest in the village, including his deaf
and dumb wife and his aged parents. With the help of the village
headquarters, the Yangs now have enough food and clothing.
</P>
<P>
Local government officials informed Xinhua that the village has
set a good example for other villages affected by the dam
project.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
