<HEADLINE> FIFA to Unveil Hall of Champions in Paris </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A Hall of Champions will be
unveiled in Paris in 1998 for the soccer's grestest players and
champions, sources from FIFA said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The complex, at a cost of 50 million US Dollars, will be housed
in an 8,500 square metre building, and comprises a multi-media
theatre, an exhibition hall and other zones featuring the
development of the sport.
</P>
<P>
To be built at Disneyland Paris, the project was under the
auspices of FIFA and International Sports and Entertainment
Concepts Incorporated of Atlanta, Georgia.
</P>
<P>
The Hall of Champions will feature a maximum of five players a
year as well as the greatest teams of all time.
</P>
<P>
In January, a panel of experts will vote for a special first
induction of 10 players who had a career of at least 10 years and
retired from the sport at least five years.
</P>
<P>
Among the obvious choices were Pele, Eusebio, Johan Cruyff,
Stanley Matthews, but Diego Maradona may be a topic of guessing.
</P>
<P>
Maradona who led Argentina to win the 1986 World Cup, had been
banned for 15 months after failing a dope test during the 1994
World Cup in the United States.
</P>
<P>
The Hall is expected to open in the spring of 1998, shortly
before the start of the World Cup finals in France. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
