<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museums in Beijing to Have Admission-Free Days </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Residents of the Chinese
capital will soon be able to visit museums free of charge on
certain days, according to the Municipal Bureau of Cultural Relics.
</P>
<P>
About 30 museums directly under the administration of the
bureau have been ordered to open to the public without charging
fees on the first Sunday of each month from March 1, said Shan
Jixiang, director of the bureau.
</P>
<P>
"We made such a decision with the aim not only of helping
citizens gain more knowledge, but to mark the 20th International
Museum Day, which will fall on May 18 this year," Shan said.
</P>
<P>
The museums display objects and pictures demonstrating the
city's 1,000-year history, historical relics, and so on.
</P>
<P>
"This action is just an experiment. More museums will be
involved next year if the experiment is successful," said Xu Ming,
an official with the bureau.
</P>
<P>
Boasting rich resources of cultural relics and serving as
China's cultural center, Beijing has 94 museums of different
types, the biggest number of any part of the country.
</P>
<P>
The museums hold 400 exhibitions annually, receiving about 40
million visitors.
</P>
<P>
Since early last year the museums have started to reduce the
prices of admission or exempt admission for students and teachers
during weekends and holidays.  
</P>
</TEXT>
