<HEADLINE> Bright Prospects for Southern Chinese Coastal Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HAIKOU, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Large-scale construction over
the last few years at Beibu Bay, which covers 1.5 million square
kilometers of land in south and southwest China areas and has a
population of 200 million, means the economy there is expected to
take off soon.
</P>
<P>
The construction of new railways, roads, and ports will link
the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region, Guangdong and Hainan
provinces more closely.
</P>
<P>
To take advantage of opportunities, Guangxi has built several
railways and five new ports. A road network linking four key
cities in the region and ports is also expected to be set up.
</P>
<P>
A new railway linking Nanning, Guangxi's capital, with Kunming,
capital of neighboring Yunnan, provides a shortcut to the sea.
</P>
<P>
Guangdong province's Zhanjiang, the largest port city in the
Beibu Bay region, has also accelerated construction. The
Zhanjiang-Hai'an highway will open this year and the construction
of the double-track Litang-Zhanjiang railway, the
Zhanjiang-Yangjiang highway, and Zhanjiang-Hai'an railway will
start.
</P>
<P>
The bay regions has also made full use of its other
advantages. Hainan province plans to increase marine economic
output value to 15 billion yuan in the year 2000 from the current
four billion yuan annually. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
