<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multi-Billion Water Project Attracting Contractors </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Engineering contractors from
14 countries are showing great interest in the construction of a
multi-billion water-diversion project in North China.
</P>
<P>
the Wanjiazhai water-diversion project is designed to channel
water from the upper reaches of the Yellow River to North China's
coal-rich province of Shanxi, which suffers from a severe shortage
of water.
</P>
<P>
The whole project will cost 20 billion yuan (about 2.41 billion
US dollars), of which the World Bank will provide 400 million US
dollars in the form of loans.
</P>
<P>
According to Zheng Yousan, general manager of the Wanjiazhai
Yellow River Water-Diversion Corporation of Shanxi Province, 14
companies have been accepted as qualified for public bidding,
during which participants will compete for the right to contract
construction of an underground pumping station and four tunnels.
</P>
<P>
The 14 companies are from Spain, Italy, Canada, New Zealand,
Austria, Switzerland, Sweden, Brazil, Germany, France, Japan,
Mexico, the Republic of Korea and China.
</P>
<P>
On February 24 more than 100 businessmen representing the 14
companies arrived in Shuozhou, Shanxi, to attend a preparatory
meeting during which participants had chances to get to know more
about the bidding items.
</P>
<P>
It is learned that competing bidders are expected to finish and
hand in their bidding documents to a professional assessment
committee in charge of the public bidding for the water project
before the afternoon of April 4 this year, and the winners will be
announced soon after.
</P>
<P>
Construction is expected to begin in September this year.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, power-generating units will be
built in Wanjiazhai Village, Pianguan County, to divert water from
the Yellow River to Taiyuan, the provincial capital, and to
Shuozhou and Datong, two industrial cities in northern Shanxi.
</P>
<P>
The project will consist of two phases. In the first phase
water will be channeled from the Yellow River, which runs from
north to south in the western part of Shanxi, to Taiyuan. It is
expected to be finished by 2001.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
