<HEADLINE> Rare Trees Win Protection in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Baoding, a historical
city in north China's Hebei Province, has conducted a survey of
local rare trees with the aim of ensuring them proper protection.
</P>
<P>
The results, issued by the local department of forestry, show
that the city now has 151 ancient rare trees, which have been
registered on a local protection list.
</P>
<P>
Leng Shiwen, a senior engineer with the department, said that
all the trees are more than 100 years old.
</P>
<P>
"Some were planted by ancient celebrities or are connected with
legendary stories," said Leng, adding that they are of great
importance for studies of local natural science, culture and
history.
</P>
<P>
Two of the trees have been included in a book called "The
Wonder of China's Ancient Trees". 
</P>
</TEXT>
