<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Private Businessmen in Shandong Help the Poor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, February 28 (Xinhua) -- An increasing number of local
private businessmen in east China's Shandong Province have taken
part in the Glory Program, a national scheme launched in 1994 by
some private entrepreneurs to help poverty-stricken areas.
</P>
<P>
By the end of 1996 over 2,000 local private industrialists had
participated in the program, with over 40 projects initiated and
involving a total investment of nearly 100 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Local private companies have also helped nearly 100 state-owned
enterprises through annexation, leasing and
contracting. Meanwhile, over 4,200 people from poor areas have
been trained by private firms.
</P>
<P>
In 1996 alone, local private businessmen donated over 58
million yuan to education, and the building of roads and bridges,
as well as welfare facilities such as homes for the aged.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, local private businessmen have also helped
introduce investment from other parts of the country for some poor
areas in the province.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures, the poverty-stricken population
in Shandong has declined from 7.6 million in 1984 to around one
million now.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
