<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shandong Vows to Eliminate Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Shandong, a populous province in
east China, has vowed to eradicate poverty within two years.
</P>
<P>
This coastal province launched an anti-poverty program in
1984. By the end of last year the provincial government had
invested 1.2 billion yuan (about 145 million US dollars) in the
program.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the number of people living under the poverty
line, (with annual per capita income of no more than 530 yuan) was
reduced from 7.6 million in 1984 to last year's one million.
</P>
<P>
From this year the provincial government will increase its
annual allocation of funds for helping the poor from the previous
20 million yuan to 50 million yuan.
</P>
<P>
Shandong plans to invest 300 million yuan in the 1997-1998
period to help people in poor counties on both sides of the Yellow
River and lakeside areas to move to better-off regions.
</P>
<P>
It has also speeded up the exploitation of natural resources in
the Yimeng mountainous area and around Dongping Lake. Government
planned investment in the development of the lake will reach 770
million yuan in the next four years. Some 37 villages in the lake
area and 630,000 people in the Yimeng area will benefit from the
two development projects.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the provincial government has worked out a series
of policies granting preferential treatment to poor counties such
as exemption of state grain quotas and agricultural tax.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0276 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PICC Property's Shanghai Branch Speeds up Commercialization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, February 28 (Xinhua) -- The People's Insurance
Company of China (PICC) Property's Shanghai branch has speeded up
its commercialization through making all of its 53 middle-level
managers into contracted employees.
</P>
<P>
The managers have signed contracts with the branch, making them
"contracted managers" under the strict disciplines of personnel
management and annual evaluation.
</P>
<P>
PICC managers used to enjoy lifelong privileges in housing,
salaries, etc.
</P>
<P>
These managers are also the first "contracted officials" in the
financial sector of this, the country's trade and financial hub,
at a time when China's opening-up of finance industry is under way.
</P>
<P>
PICC Property is one of the three subsidiaries of the former
state insurance company PICC, which is heading for
commercialization.
</P>
<P>
PICC Property's Shanghai branch now controls 60 percent of the
local property insurance business, and generated 1.85 billion yuan
in income last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0277 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Finds Ways to Help Poor College Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, February 28 (Xinhua) -- Beijing's colleges and
universities have been helping poor students to continue their
studies since China adopted a self-paying system for college
education.
</P>
<P>
Statistics from the Beijing Education Commission (BEC) show
that the city's 67 universities and colleges have about 13,000
poor students, or more than one tenth of the total college
students if the above-poverty income level is set at 120 yuan
(14.4 US dollars) per capita monthly in their families.
</P>
<P>
In some schools in the Chinese capital poor students account
for 30 percent of the enrollment.
</P>
<P>
The BEC has funneled an annual fund of 39.19 million yuan
(about 4.72 million US dollars) in recent years into schools by
offering scholarships for students who study and behave well, said
Gan Beilin, who is in charge of college students' guidance.
</P>
<P>
Recent years have seen nearly 98,000 scholarship winners, with
500 students obtaining four local particular study awards, he said.
</P>
<P>
Some 41 schools have set up student loans with a total fund of
12.88 million yuan, which has helped nearly 1,000 poor students
overcome financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
Gan said that 9,000 part-time jobs have been provided for over
20,000 college students annually. Under this program, more than
3,000 poor students have managed to make ends meet.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, the state has issued grant-in-aid worth 2.42
million yuan to needy students via schools in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Reduction of tuition fees has also helped poor students, Gan
added.
</P>
<P>
BEC officials, however, said that not all the city's higher
schools face the same problem. Some schools under the municipality
have fewer students who need aid, because most are Beijingers,
whose families have more income than other places in China.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, some reputed schools, such as Qinghua, Beijing and
the People's University, have solved their problems concerning
needy students, thanks to more grants from society and the better
organizing of part-time jobs for the poor.
</P>
<P>
But students majoring in agriculture, geology, mining, Chinese
traditional medicine and teaching still face financial challenges.
</P>
<P>
The BEC will put aside a special fund and scholarships for poor
college students in 1997, when China will discontinue its
long-term system of state sponsorship for college students, Gan
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0278 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
