<HEADLINE> UN Council Calls for Cessation of Hostilities in Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security Council
on Thursday urged Somali factions to cooperate with regional peace
efforts and cease immediately all hostilities.
</P>
<P>
"The Security Council reaffirms its commitment to a
comprehensive and lasting settlement of the situation in Somalia,"
said a presidential statement.
</P>
<P>
"It reiterates that full responsibility for achieving national
reconciliation and for restoring peace rests with the Somali
people," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Ali Mahdi Mohamed, a clan leader from the northern half of the
divided capital of Mogadishu, and Hussein Aidid, who controls
parts of south Mogadishu, agreed in January to abide by a
cease-fire negotiated Oct. 15 in Nairobi. But fighting has
persisted, despite the agreement.
</P>
<P>
The council called upon Somali factions to ensure safety and
movement of aid workers and facilitate delivery of relief supplies
by opening Mogadishu's airport and harbor.
</P>
<P>
It also reiterated its call upon all states to fulfill their
obligation to implement the embargo imposed by resolution 733 on
all deliveries of weapons and military equipment to Somalia.
</P>
</TEXT>
