<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Slide Again </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street slid
again today as bonds fell for the second straight session amid
growing worries about a potential interest rate hike next month.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average lost 58.11 points to 6,925.07.
</P>
<P>
Decliners outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-4 margin on the New
York Stock Exchange, with NYSE volume down to 464.68 million
shares, from 566.31 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 10.60 to 795.08, and
the NYSE's composite index fell 4.25 to 417.89.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index fell 27.82 to 1,312.73, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.14 to 595.17.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, stocks tumbled with bonds after another warning
by Federal Reserve chairman Greenspan that the stock market's
surprising gains pose an inflationary risk. It was the second time
in less than three months that Greenspan sent the market into a
panic.
</P>
<P>
A series of surprisingly strong economic readings has fanned
worries about inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
Today, the Commerce Department reported that orders to U.S.
factories for big-ticket durable goods shot up 3.6 percent in
January, the first advance in three months and the largest since
September.
</P>
<P>
Analysts also said the labor market continued its strength.
</P>
<P>
The two most active Nasdaq issues were networking concern 3Com
and modem maker U.S. Robotics, which announced a 6.6 billion U.S.
dollar merger agreement after the close of Wednesday's trading.
</P>
</TEXT>
