<HEADLINE> French Auto Producer to Close Factory in Belgium </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- France's auto producer Renault
will close in July its oldest overseas factory in Vilvorde,
Belgium, because of heavy budget deficit and fierce competition of
the European auto market.
</P>
<P>
The close of Vilvorde factory, which is located near Brussels
and was established in 1925, will cost Belgium 3,100 jobs and
immediately caused worry from French unions over more close-downs
of factories and mass lay-offs.
</P>
<P>
The closing of Vilvorde factory signals the beginning of a
restructuring program and a specialization plan of its factories
by Renault, whose budget has been in the red since 1995.
</P>
<P>
A Renault spokesman said today that the group, which will
announce soon a "very significant loss" of money in 1996, has to
"simplify and better use its industrial tool."
</P>
<P>
The fourth largest auto producer in Europe and with 46 percent
of its shares still being held by the French state, Renault has
been losing market over the past two years because of retardedness
in renovation of its range and high production costs.
</P>
<P>
Renault had to lower its automobile prices last September in
order to survive fierce competition from other European cars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, its leaders are trying to rationalize its production
apparatus in order to fully exploit its capacity by improving the
performances of its factories and lowering production costs.
</P>
</TEXT>
