<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Names New Humanitarian Coordinator for Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 27 (Xinhua) - Staffan de Mistura, a
national of Sweden and a veteran U.N. official for relief
assistance, was named on Thursday as the new coordinator for
humanitarian aid in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
In announcing the appointment, U.N. spokesman Juan Carlos
Brandt said de Mistura is expected to take up his new post in the
next few days, replacing Gualtiero Gulcheri of Italy, who left
Baghdad on Monday.
</P>
<P>
De Mistura is to supervise the complex oil-for-food program
in Iraq that involves U.N. monitors checking on food, medicine and
other goods for the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Under the program, Iraq is permitted to sell $2 billion worth
of oil over six months to buy needed supplies for its people, who
have suffered under trade sanctions since August 1990.
</P>
<P>
Mr. de Mistura has had long experience in humanitarian work in
the U.N. system, serving with the U.N. Children's Fund, the World
Food Program, the U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization and the
U.N. Development program.
</P>
<P>
He was the chief U.N. humanitarian coordinator in northern Iraq
in June, 1991 and served in Somalia in 1992-1994, supervising all
U.N. humanitarian aid there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
