<HEADLINE> Saudis Renews Cooperation Assurance in Bomb Probe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Saudi Arabia reassured the
United States on Thursday that Riyadh will continue to cooperate
with Washington in the investigation into the June 25 truck
bombing, 1996, at the Khobar barracks in an air base near Dhahran,
that killed 19 U.S. servicemen.
</P>
<P>
The renewed pledge came from Saudi Deputy Prime Minister and
Defense Minister Prince Sultan when he held talks with Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright this morning.
</P>
<P>
"Prince Sultan and his associates pledged full cooperation by
the Saudi authorities with the FBI and other agencies of the U.S.
government," State Department spokesman Nicholas Burns told a
regular news briefing. "We were very pleased to receive these
assurances, and we are counting on continued Saudi cooperation in
the future."
</P>
<P>
Prince Sultan has repeated his government's pledge to U.S.
leaders including President Bill Clinton and Defense Secretary
William Cohen when he discussed the issue with them during his
five-day visit to Washington, in a bid to alleviate U.S.
frustrations over what U.S. investigators there complained was
lack of information provided for them for the probe into who were
responsible for the bomb attack.
</P>
<P>
Burns said the United States expects the cooperation would
continue as Prince Sultan has assured in his "face-to-face"
meeting with U.S. leaders this week.
</P>
<P>
Burns revealed that Prince Sultan had discussed with Albright
about the Middle East peace negotiations, and the Clinton
administration was "very pleased to learn today that the Saudi
government intends to continue its large economic assistance to
the Palestinians in the West Bank."
</P>
<P>
Iraq was also a topic in Albright's talks with Prince Sultan
and "there was complete agreement between the Saudis and
Americans that we ought to continue to apply the sanctions on
Iraq,... until Iraq meets all of the relevant commitments under
all the relevant U.N. Security Council resolutions," Burns
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
