<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Investigates Companies Compromising Helms-Burton Act </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The European Union fears that
dozens of European companies are breaking EU laws and undermining
its effort to counter the U.S. Helms-Burton Act aimed at Cuba, it
was learned here today.
</P>
<P>
The dozens of companies, which are keeping the matter quiet,
are being investigated by the European Commission, the EU's
executive body, trade sources said in Brussels Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to an EU spokesman, the EU legislation to combat the
Helms sanctions "was law and had to be followed up." The
Commission has expressed its deep disappointment with the lack of
support it is getting from those companies in fighting
Helms-Burton.
</P>
<P>
Peter Guilford, spokesman for the EU trade commissioner, Sir
Leon Brittan, said that the anti-blocking legislation was a
powerful response to Helms-Burton, which has put companies in a
difficult position.
</P>
<P>
But he added, "In order to make it effective we have to dig."
The law was passed in October to combat the Helms-Burton Act,
which is aimed at further isolating the Cuban government of Fidel
Castro.
</P>
<P>
Under the Helms-Burton, naturalized Americans are entitled to
sue any foreign company or individual who have made profits out of
investments in property confiscated by the Cuban government after
the 1959 revolution.
</P>
<P>
By passing legislation to counter the act, the EU has made it
illegal for European companies to cooperate with any U.S.
investigation and to prevent companies from withdrawing from Cuba
due to a U.S. inquiry.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. State Department has reportedly compiled a blacklist
of foreign companies that might be investing in such property.
Executives from the Italian telecom company STET, the Canadian
mining conglomerate Sherrit International and the Mexican telecom
company Grupo Domo have been barred from entering the U.S. because
of their links to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
Washington declined to tell the number and the names of the
companies which it has put on its watch list, but it was reported
that the actual number was far more than the three, which were
identified in 1996. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
