<HEADLINE> Annan: UN Begins Distributing Food in Iraq March 1st </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Secretary
General Kofi Annan said here this evening that the United Nations
will begin distributing food in Iraq on March 1st, in application
of the "Oil for Food" plan it signed with Baghdad last May.
</P>
<P>
Following a three-hour meeting with French Prime Minister Alain
Juppe, Annan told the press that the preparations for food
distribution "are going on quite well," but he stressed that the
U.N. is following the situation of Iraq "very closely."
</P>
<P>
"We have talked about the efforts by the United Nations to
distribute humanitarian products, as well as this question of sale
of oil (by Iraq)... We will begin from March 1st," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations nominated Swedish Staffan de Mistura as U.N.
humanitarian coordinator in Iraq to be in charge of applying the
"Oil for Food" plan.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations said that de Mistura will arrive in Baghdad
in the coming days, while one third of the U.N. observers for the
application of the plan have arrived there.
</P>
<P>
The plan allows Iraq to sell 2 billion U.S. dollars of oil in
six months to buy food and medical materials desperately needed by
the Iraqi people, who have been suffering from hunger and diseases
since the U.N. imposed an economic sanction in 1990 in reaction to
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations plans to deploy 151 observers for
distributing food, 23 customs officials for checking the arrival
of cargos and 14 inspectors for supervising Iraq's exporting of
oil.
</P>
<P>
A staff of eight U.N. officials will be coordinating the
application of the plan from the U.N. New York headquarters.
</P>
</TEXT>
