<HEADLINE> UN Council Renews Angola Peace Force for Only a Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The U.N. Security
Council on Thursday renewed the mandate of the U.N. peace-keeping
force in Angola for only one month, until March 31 because the
former UNITA rebels delays in establishing a national unity
government in the country.
</P>
<P>
The move was taken at the suggestion of Secretary-General Kofi
Annan. He said in a recent report he would recommend a two-month
extension of the U.N. force if the national unity government were
formed before its expiry at the end of February.
</P>
<P>
Otherwise, he recommended only a one-month renewal, until the
end of March.
</P>
<P>
In a unanimous resolution, the council warned that it was
ready, in case of further delay, to impose trade sanctions on
UNITA and travel restrictions on its senior officials.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Angolan Verification Mission (UNAVEM III), now has
more than 6,000 troops, observers and police, has been helping
oversee a peace accord which the government led by President Jose
Eduardo dos Santos signed with UNITA in Lusaka Zambia, in 1994.
</P>
<P>
Establishment of a national unity government, originally
scheduled for January 25, was postponed, largely because of
problems in finding an acceptable role for UNITA leader Jonas
Savimbi, who still controls much of Angola, including diamond-rich
areas.
</P>
<P>
The Security Council resolution expressed deep concern at the
second delay in forming a national unity government "as a result
of the failure of UNITA" to meet an agreed timetable.
</P>
<P>
It urged the "government of Angola and in particular UNITA to
solve the remaining military and other issues and to establish,
without further delay, the government of unity and national
reconciliation."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
