<HEADLINE> EU Official Welcomes Self-Medication </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- A well-developed
self-medication can contribute to a higher level of health
protection, an EU official said here today.
</P>
<P>
Padraig Flynn, EU commissioner for social affairs, made the
remark Thursday at a conference on defining the scope of
responsible self-medication.
</P>
<P>
"Self-medication, if sensibly developed, can contribute to a
higher level of health protection. In particular, it allows for
greater scope for the individual to take responsibility for his
own health," he said.
</P>
<P>
Mr. Flynn said that self-medication could ease the pressure on
doctors and the health services which were increasingly
over-stretched.
</P>
<P>
He went on to stress that self-medication was of particular
benefit in the treatment of minor ailments and illnesses, but it
was "not a solution for more serious conditions."
</P>
<P>
He warned the public that they should be aware of the need to
consult a doctor if in doubt or if symptoms persist, adding that
"on issues of health, precaution must always come first."
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the continued upward pressure in public health
expenditure, the commissioner said that the question of the need
for cost-containment should not be under-estimated, and added that
"more self-care in circumstances of minor ailments can reduce the
burden on health services."  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
