<HEADLINE> Clinton, Yeltsin set Agenda for Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin agreed today in a telephone
conversation on a three-part agenda for the Helsinki summit
scheduled next month.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents agreed to focus on European security,
reduction of nuclear arms and economic reforms in Russia when they
meet, David Johnson, a White House spokesman, told reporters.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents spoke at about noon EST for about 20
minutes, according to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
"This is part of a continuing pattern of consultations that the
United States and the Russian Federation have had as we lead up to
the summit in Helsinki, " added the spokesman.
</P>
<P>
"We're going to have expert teams from the United States
traveling to Moscow over the course of the next few weeks, in
advance of the summit, on all three of those agenda items, " he
said.
</P>
<P>
The teams will talk about how will be a NATO-Russian charter
and how Russia and U.S. deal with other issues related to NATO
expansion, according to Johnson.
</P>
<P>
The U.S.-Russian summit, scheduled on March 20-21, is taking
place at a time when the North Atlantic Treaty Organization (NATO)
is planning to expand into the Central and Eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
Moscow has been signaling strong opposition to the enlargement,
insisting that its national security is threatened.
</P>
<P>
However, reports say that Russia, which has taken a two-tiered
approach to the issue, seems to be putting fresh emphasis on
negotiating a compromise. 
</P>
</TEXT>
