<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> French National Assembly Adopts New Immigration Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, February 27 (Xinhua) -- The French National Assembly
(lower house of parliament) adopted this evening the strongly
contested new immigration law presented by Interior Minister
Jean-Louis Debre, after three days of heated debate.
</P>
<P>
However, the first and most controversial clause of the law,
which asked French homes to inform police the time of departure
from France of foreigners they had accommodated, was scrapped by
the president of the law commission of the parliament, Pierre
Mazeaud.
</P>
<P>
The clause triggered a wide-spread civil disobedience movement
and nationwide streets protests, initiated by some movie producers
who protested first the restriction of their invited foreigners
to work with them.
</P>
<P>
The corrected law, also called Debre bill in reference to the
interior minister, asks foreigners themselves to hand over to
French border police a registration card proving they have
left France.
</P>
<P>
The law was passed with 113 votes from the ruling rightwing
majority, and 61 votes against from the opposition leftwing
parties.
</P>
<P>
The Agence France-Presse (AFP) said that today's voting
contrasted with the first voting of the law in late December, when
most of the Socialist deputies were absent and let the law slip
through with an overwhelming support from the ruling majority.
</P>
<P>
A dramatic confrontation was seen on Wednesday between Interior
Minister Debre and the president of the Socialist group of
parliament, former Socialist prime minister Laurent Fabius, who
forced Debre to admit that the government intends to set up an
index system for all foreigner who have stayed in France.
</P>
<P>
The law has also drawn criticism from the European Parliament,
which voted last week that it should be withdrawn because it
reminded one of "invitation of denunciations" of foreigners of
old times.
</P>
<P>
Some French leftist politicians and intellectuals compared the
law with the persecution of Jews during the World War II Vichy
collaboration regime, which deported thousands of French Jews to
Nazi death camps.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, the law was presented at a time when the far-right
National Front party, which publicly advocates the expulsion of
foreign immigrants, is rising on the political stage of France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970228.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-02-28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Frei Calls for Higher-level Chilean-U.S. Trade Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Chilean President
Eduardo Frei today, calling his nation as a platform for trade in
Latin America, urged the United States to hold higher-level
negotiations with his country on free trade deal.
</P>
<P>
"Our trade negotiations with the United States are of great
interest to us and we believe they should advance to higher
levels," said Frei in a speech before a joint meeting of U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
"Before this Congress, let me reaffirm our interest in those
negotiations," Frei said. "We consider total trade liberalization
between Chile and the United States a natural step, as well as an
encouraging signal in the task of achieving free trade in
Americas."
</P>
<P>
Chile was invited in December, 1994, to join the United States,
Mexico and Canada in the North American Free Trade Agreement
(NAFTA). But it wants Congress to give the U.S. administration
"fast-track" authority to cut a deal that would be voted on
without any amendments. The authority ensures that a trade pact
would get a straight yes-or-no vote.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton said Wednesday after meeting Frei
in the White House that he was seeking the "fast-track" trade
negotiation authority from Congress to conclude new trade
agreements that "open markets to America's products.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said unless Congress quickly renews his authority to
expand NAFTA, the United States risks losing to European and Asian
competitors already moving into America's economic back yard.
</P>
<P>
But some politicians fear that an expanded NAFTA would increase
U.S. import from Latin American nations which would lead to losing
job opportunities in the country.
</P>
<P>
House of Representatives Minority leader Richard Gephardt, a
Missouri Democrat, wrote in a letter to his Democratic colleagues
on Wednesday that it would be "a fundamental mistake to simply
extend the current NAFTA. It simply isn't working."
</P>
<P>
But Frei said, "delays (of trade negotiations) today could mean
the weakening of many democracies, the rebirth of closed markets,
the consolidation of hunger and migrations." 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
