<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US President Appeals for Balancing Budget Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, February 27 (Xinhua) -- With the balanced budget
Constitutional amendment on its deathbed, President Clinton today
appealed to the U.S. Congress for passing a balancing budget plan
this year.
</P>
<P>
In a speech to the U.S. Business Council, President Clinton
called on the Republicans in the Congress to quickly move away
from the politically divisive debate.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Senator Robert Torricelli announced Wednesday that he
couldn't accept the Republican version of Constitutional amendment
because he thought it left the nation too vulnerable in times of
military or economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
He was considered the decisive 67th vote that was needed for
the two-thirds majority for passage the balanced budget amendment
in the U.S. Senate.
</P>
<P>
"It now seems clear that the balanced budget amendment will not
pass. I think that is a good thing for the reasons that I have
said elsewhere," President Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
"But I think it must also be clear to the American people that
we must make sure that a balanced budget does pass, passes this
year and passes as soon as we can reasonably pass it," he said.
"We have to now go beyond the constitutional debate to get to the
specifics."
</P>
<P>
The balanced budget Constitutional amendment is scheduled to
put on vote in the U.S. senate next Tuesday, the probable date of
a final vote. But without the vote of Torricelli, the amendment
could face the same fate it met two years ago, when a balanced
budget amendment was defeated by one vote in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
Republican leaders are still trying to change somebody's mind.
But the chief sponsor of the bill, Senate Judiciary Committee
Chairman Orrin Hatch showed little interest in making concessions
to bring another Democrat on board. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
